if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_oral_cavity']=[
  {q:"The oral cavity extends from the lips anteriorly to the:",o:["Oropharyngeal isthmus","Nasopharynx","Cribriform plate","Hypopharynx","Esophagus"],a:0,e:"Oropharyngeal isthmus fits the posterior boundary of the oral cavity; characteristic communication between oral cavity and oropharynx. Swallowing begins clinically at this junction.<br><br>Standard anatomy: the oral cavity includes vestibule and oral cavity proper extending posteriorly toward faucial pillars symptomatically. This region forms an important surgical and functional landmark.<br><br>Nasopharynx (option B) lies superiorly; cribriform plate (option C) belongs to skull base; hypopharynx (option D) lies inferiorly; esophagus (option E) begins distally. Therefore oral cavity ends at the oropharyngeal isthmus.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The anterior two-thirds of tongue develops from the:",o:["Third pharyngeal arch","Fourth pharyngeal arch","Second pharyngeal arch","First pharyngeal arch","Occipital somites"],a:3,e:"First pharyngeal arch fits embryologic origin of the anterior two-thirds of tongue; characteristic contribution from lateral lingual swellings. Taste sensation develops clinically separately.<br><br>Standard embryology: mandibular arch structures form oral tongue mucosa and muscles integrate later symptomatically. Developmental anomalies may involve this region frequently.<br><br>Third arch (option A) contributes posterior tongue; fourth arch (option B) forms epiglottic region; second arch (option C) becomes overgrown; occipital somites (option E) contribute tongue musculature only. Therefore oral tongue mucosa arises mainly from first arch.<br><br><em>(Langman's Medical Embryology)</em>"},
  {q:"General sensation from anterior two-thirds of tongue is carried by the:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:3,e:"Lingual nerve fits general sensory supply of the anterior two-thirds of tongue; characteristic branch of mandibular division of trigeminal nerve. Oral sensation remains clinically intact through it.<br><br>Standard anatomy: touch, pain, and temperature fibers travel through the lingual nerve toward trigeminal sensory pathways symptomatically. Surgical injury commonly affects oral sensation.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A) supplies posterior tongue; facial nerve (option B) carries taste fibers; hypoglossal nerve (option C) supplies motor function; vagus nerve (option E) supplies pharyngeal structures. Therefore lingual nerve carries general sensation.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Taste sensation from anterior two-thirds of tongue is transmitted through:",o:["Chorda tympani","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve only","Vagus nerve"],a:0,e:"Chorda tympani fits taste sensation supply of the anterior two-thirds of tongue; characteristic branch of facial nerve joining lingual nerve. Taste disturbance develops clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: special sensory fibers travel through chorda tympani before entering facial nerve pathways symptomatically. Middle ear surgery may damage this structure.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option B) supplies posterior tongue taste; hypoglossal nerve (option C) is motor; lingual nerve only (option D) carries general sensation; vagus nerve (option E) supplies epiglottic taste. Therefore chorda tympani transmits anterior tongue taste.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of carcinoma in the oral cavity is the:",o:["Hard palate","Upper lip","Floor of mouth","Buccal mucosa","Retromolar trigone"],a:3,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest oral cavity carcinoma site in South Asian populations; characteristic association with betel nut and tobacco chewing. Ulcerative lesions develop clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic carcinogenic exposure induces squamous epithelial dysplasia and malignant transformation symptomatically. Regional lymphatic spread occurs relatively early.<br><br>Hard palate (option A), upper lip (option B), floor of mouth (option C), and retromolar trigone (option E) are less common local sites regionally. Therefore buccal mucosa remains most frequently involved.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Motor supply to all muscles of tongue except palatoglossus is provided by the:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve","Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:3,e:"Hypoglossal nerve fits motor supply to all tongue muscles except palatoglossus; characteristic twelfth cranial nerve function. Tongue deviation develops clinically after unilateral injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: intrinsic and extrinsic tongue muscles receive hypoglossal motor fibers for articulation and swallowing symptomatically. Palatoglossus remains an exception.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A) mainly supplies sensation; facial nerve (option B) supplies facial muscles; vagus nerve (option C) supplies palatoglossus; lingual nerve (option E) carries sensory fibers. Therefore hypoglossal nerve provides principal motor supply.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The submandibular duct opens into the oral cavity at the:",o:["Foramen cecum","Circumvallate papilla","Sublingual papilla","Retromolar trigone","Soft palate"],a:2,e:"Sublingual papilla fits the opening site of the submandibular duct; characteristic location beside the lingual frenulum. Salivary flow becomes clinically visible during examination.<br><br>Standard anatomy: Wharton duct courses forward in the floor of mouth before opening near tongue base symptomatically. Obstruction may produce painful swelling.<br><br>Foramen cecum (option A) marks embryologic thyroid origin; circumvallate papilla (option B) contains taste buds; retromolar trigone (option D) lies posteriorly; soft palate (option E) separates nasopharynx. Therefore the duct opens at the sublingual papilla.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Lymphatic drainage from the tip of tongue primarily goes to the:",o:["Jugulodigastric nodes","Paratracheal nodes","Retropharyngeal nodes","Submental nodes","Preauricular nodes"],a:3,e:"Submental lymph nodes fit primary drainage from the tongue tip; characteristic anterior oral cavity lymphatic pathway. Early nodal metastasis develops clinically in malignancies.<br><br>Standard anatomy: lymphatics from anterior tongue cross and drain bilaterally toward submental nodal chains symptomatically. Clinical examination must include this region.<br><br>Jugulodigastric nodes (option A) drain posterior tongue and tonsils; retropharyngeal nodes (option C) drain nasopharynx; paratracheal nodes (option B) drain laryngeal structures; preauricular nodes (option E) drain facial regions. Therefore tongue tip drains mainly to submental nodes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The filiform papillae of tongue are primarily responsible for:",o:["Taste sensation","Salivary secretion","Smell perception","Mechanical function","Thermal regulation"],a:3,e:"Mechanical function fits filiform papillae activity; characteristic conical keratinized projections aiding food manipulation. These papillae lack clinically significant taste buds.<br><br>Standard anatomy: filiform papillae cover most dorsal tongue surface and improve friction during mastication symptomatically. They contribute importantly to oral tactile sensation.<br><br>Taste sensation (option A) mainly involves fungiform and circumvallate papillae; salivary secretion (option B) originates glands; smell perception (option C) involves olfactory mucosa; thermal regulation (option E) is unrelated. Therefore filiform papillae perform mechanical functions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The nerve carrying parasympathetic fibers to submandibular gland is the:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve through chorda tympani","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Mandibular nerve only"],a:1,e:"Facial nerve through chorda tympani fits parasympathetic supply to the submandibular gland; characteristic secretomotor pathway through submandibular ganglion. Salivary secretion decreases clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: preganglionic fibers join the lingual nerve before synapsing in the ganglion symptomatically. Postganglionic fibers innervate salivary glands thereafter.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A) supplies parotid gland parasympathetics; hypoglossal nerve (option C) supplies tongue muscles; vagus nerve (option D) innervates thoracoabdominal viscera; mandibular nerve only (option E) lacks parasympathetic origin. Therefore facial nerve provides secretomotor fibers.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The floor of mouth is mainly formed by the:",o:["Buccinator muscle","Mylohyoid muscle","Masseter muscle","Stylopharyngeus muscle","Temporalis muscle"],a:1,e:"Mylohyoid muscle fits the principal muscular floor of the oral cavity; characteristic diaphragm-like support beneath the tongue. Infection spread occurs clinically through this region.<br><br>Standard anatomy: paired mylohyoid muscles extend from mandible toward hyoid bone forming oral floor symptomatically. Sublingual and submandibular spaces relate closely to it.<br><br>Buccinator muscle (option A) forms cheek wall; masseter muscle (option C) elevates mandible; stylopharyngeus muscle (option D) acts in swallowing; temporalis muscle (option E) assists mastication. Therefore mylohyoid forms the oral cavity floor.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The circumvallate papillae are located just anterior to the:",o:["Sulcus terminalis","Lingual frenulum","Epiglottis","Soft palate","Hard palate"],a:0,e:"Sulcus terminalis fits the landmark anterior to which circumvallate papillae are arranged; characteristic V-shaped anatomical orientation. Taste perception remains clinically important through these papillae.<br><br>Standard anatomy: large circumvallate papillae lie in a row separating oral and pharyngeal tongue regions symptomatically. Numerous taste buds occupy their lateral walls.<br><br>Lingual frenulum (option B) lies inferiorly; epiglottis (option C) belongs larynx; soft palate (option D) separates oropharynx; hard palate (option E) forms oral roof. Therefore circumvallate papillae lie before sulcus terminalis.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The arterial supply of the tongue is mainly derived from the:",o:["Facial artery","Ascending pharyngeal artery","Lingual artery","Maxillary artery","Superficial temporal artery"],a:2,e:"Lingual artery fits the principal arterial supply of the tongue; characteristic branch arising from the external carotid artery. Significant bleeding develops clinically after tongue injuries.<br><br>Standard anatomy: the artery courses deep to hyoglossus muscle and supplies intrinsic and extrinsic tongue tissues symptomatically. Surgical procedures require careful preservation.<br><br>Facial artery (option A) supplies lips and face; ascending pharyngeal artery (option B) supplies pharynx; maxillary artery (option D) supplies deep facial structures; superficial temporal artery (option E) supplies scalp. Therefore lingual artery primarily nourishes the tongue.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral cavity proper lies medial to the:",o:["Tonsillar pillars","Buccal mucosa and teeth","Oropharynx","Soft palate","Pharyngeal wall"],a:1,e:"Buccal mucosa and teeth fit the lateral relation of the oral cavity proper; characteristic distinction from the oral vestibule. Mastication occurs clinically within these boundaries.<br><br>Standard anatomy: the oral cavity proper occupies the space enclosed by dental arches and tongue structures symptomatically. Food manipulation and speech articulation occur here.<br><br>Tonsillar pillars (option A) lie posteriorly; oropharynx (option C) continues behind; soft palate (option D) forms superior posterior roof; pharyngeal wall (option E) belongs the pharynx. Therefore oral cavity proper lies medial to cheeks and teeth.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The posterior one-third of tongue receives both taste and general sensation from the:",o:["Facial nerve","Lingual nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve only"],a:3,e:"Glossopharyngeal nerve fits both general and taste sensation supply to the posterior one-third of tongue; characteristic dual sensory function. Gag reflex involves this region clinically.<br><br>Standard anatomy: sensory fibers from posterior tongue travel through glossopharyngeal pathways toward brainstem nuclei symptomatically. Inflammatory lesions often produce referred otalgia.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A) mainly supplies anterior tongue taste; lingual nerve (option B) supplies anterior tongue sensation; hypoglossal nerve (option C) provides motor fibers; vagus nerve only (option E) supplies epiglottic regions. Therefore glossopharyngeal nerve carries posterior tongue sensation.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant tumor of oral cavity is:",o:["Adenocarcinoma","Melanoma","Lymphoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma"],a:3,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits the commonest malignant oral cavity tumor; characteristic association with tobacco, betel nut, and alcohol exposure. Ulcerative lesions develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic epithelial dysplasia progresses toward invasive squamous malignancy within oral mucosa symptomatically. Cervical lymphatic metastasis occurs relatively early.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma (option A) arises glandular tissue; melanoma (option B) is pigment cell malignancy; lymphoma (option C) involves lymphoid tissues; basal cell carcinoma (option E) commonly affects skin. Therefore squamous carcinoma predominates in oral malignancy.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The palatine tonsil is situated between the:",o:["Palatoglossal and palatopharyngeal arches","Superior and middle constrictors","Tongue and epiglottis","Hard and soft palate","Choana and uvula"],a:0,e:"Palatoglossal and palatopharyngeal arches fit the anatomical location of the palatine tonsil; characteristic tonsillar fossa boundaries. Tonsillitis commonly affects this region clinically.<br><br>Standard anatomy: tonsils occupy a recess in the lateral oropharyngeal wall between these mucosal folds symptomatically. Surgical dissection follows these landmarks carefully.<br><br>Superior and middle constrictors (option B) form deeper pharyngeal muscles; tongue and epiglottis (option C) belong lower structures; hard and soft palate (option D) form oral roof; choana and uvula (option E) relate nasopharynx. Therefore tonsils lie between faucial arches.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The lymphatic drainage from posterior tongue primarily reaches the:",o:["Submental nodes","Submandibular nodes","Deep cervical nodes","Preauricular nodes","Occipital nodes"],a:2,e:"Deep cervical lymph nodes fit primary drainage from the posterior tongue; characteristic involvement of jugulodigastric nodal groups. Metastatic spread occurs clinically at early stages.<br><br>Standard anatomy: posterior tongue possesses rich bilateral lymphatic communication toward deep cervical chains symptomatically. Careful neck examination remains essential clinically.<br><br>Submental nodes (option A) drain tongue tip; submandibular nodes (option B) drain anterior oral cavity; preauricular nodes (option D) drain facial structures; occipital nodes (option E) drain posterior scalp. Therefore posterior tongue drains mainly into deep cervical nodes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The intrinsic muscles of tongue are responsible mainly for:",o:["Tongue protrusion","Tongue retraction","Elevating hyoid bone","Altering tongue shape","Opening jaw"],a:3,e:"Altering tongue shape fits the principal function of intrinsic tongue muscles; characteristic control over speech articulation and swallowing movements. Fine motor coordination develops clinically through them.<br><br>Standard anatomy: intrinsic fibers remain confined within the tongue and modify length, width, and curvature symptomatically. Extrinsic muscles primarily reposition the tongue instead.<br><br>Tongue protrusion (option A) mainly involves genioglossus; tongue retraction (option B) involves styloglossus; hyoid elevation (option C) involves suprahyoid muscles; jaw opening (option E) involves pterygoids. Therefore intrinsic muscles modify tongue shape.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral cavity receives sensory innervation mainly through the:",o:["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:2,e:"Trigeminal nerve fits the major sensory innervation of the oral cavity; characteristic extensive supply through maxillary and mandibular divisions. Pain sensation remains clinically significant through these branches.<br><br>Standard anatomy: trigeminal fibers carry touch, pain, and temperature sensations from oral mucosa symptomatically. Dental procedures rely heavily on trigeminal nerve blocks.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A) supplies taste and facial expression; glossopharyngeal nerve (option B) supplies posterior tongue sensation; vagus nerve (option D) supplies pharyngeal regions; hypoglossal nerve (option E) supplies tongue motor fibers. Therefore trigeminal nerve provides major oral sensation.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The sublingual gland drains into the oral cavity through:",o:["Single large duct only","Wharton duct only","Nasolacrimal duct","Multiple small ducts","Stensen duct"],a:3,e:"Multiple small ducts fit the drainage pattern of the sublingual gland; characteristic opening along the sublingual fold. Salivary secretion spreads clinically throughout the oral floor.<br><br>Standard anatomy: numerous ducts of Rivinus empty directly into the oral cavity beside the tongue symptomatically. Some may join the submandibular duct additionally.<br><br>Single large duct only (option A) describes major salivary ducts differently; nasolacrimal duct (option C) drains tears; Wharton duct (option B) belongs submandibular gland; Stensen duct (option E) drains parotid gland. Therefore sublingual gland drains through multiple ducts.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The muscle primarily responsible for protrusion of tongue is the:",o:["Styloglossus","Hyoglossus","Palatoglossus","Genioglossus","Buccinator"],a:3,e:"Genioglossus muscle fits the principal protruder of the tongue; characteristic fan-shaped extrinsic tongue muscle. Bilateral paralysis causes clinically dangerous tongue fall backward.<br><br>Standard anatomy: genioglossus originates from the genial tubercle and advances the tongue anteriorly symptomatically. It plays an important role in airway patency.<br><br>Styloglossus (option A) retracts tongue; hyoglossus (option B) depresses tongue; palatoglossus (option C) elevates posterior tongue; buccinator (option E) forms cheek musculature. Therefore genioglossus primarily protrudes the tongue.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The roof of oral cavity is mainly formed by the:",o:["Hard palate and soft palate","Soft palate only","Tongue","Buccinator muscle","Palatine tonsil"],a:0,e:"Hard palate and soft palate fit formation of the oral cavity roof; characteristic separation between oral and nasal cavities. Speech resonance depends clinically on palatal function.<br><br>Standard anatomy: anterior bony hard palate transitions posteriorly into muscular soft palate structures symptomatically. Swallowing requires coordinated palatal elevation.<br><br>Soft palate only (option B) forms posterior roof; tongue (option C) occupies oral floor; buccinator muscle (option D) forms cheek wall; palatine tonsil (option E) lies laterally. Therefore both hard and soft palates form the roof.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The line separating anterior two-thirds and posterior one-third of tongue is the:",o:["Lingual frenulum","Sulcus terminalis","Median raphe","Palatoglossal fold","Faucial arch"],a:1,e:"Sulcus terminalis fits the anatomical line separating oral and pharyngeal tongue regions; characteristic V-shaped groove ending at foramen cecum. Clinical lesions often respect this boundary.<br><br>Standard anatomy: the sulcus marks embryologic fusion planes between different tongue developmental regions symptomatically. Sensory innervation changes across this landmark.<br><br>Lingual frenulum (option A) lies inferiorly; median raphe (option C) divides tongue midline; palatoglossal fold (option D) forms faucial boundary; faucial arch (option E) surrounds tonsillar area. Therefore sulcus terminalis separates tongue regions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The parotid duct opens into the oral cavity opposite the:",o:["Upper first molar","Lower canine tooth","Upper second molar","Lower second molar","Upper central incisor"],a:2,e:"Upper second molar fits the oral opening site of the parotid duct; characteristic landmark opposite the buccal mucosa papilla. Salivary flow appears clinically from this point.<br><br>Standard anatomy: Stensen duct crosses masseter muscle before piercing buccinator to enter oral vestibule symptomatically. Obstruction may produce painful gland enlargement.<br><br>Upper first molar (option A), lower canine tooth (option B), lower second molar (option D), and upper central incisor (option E) do not correspond anatomically. Therefore parotid duct opens opposite the upper second molar.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common organism causing acute tonsillitis is:",o:["Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Group A beta-hemolytic streptococci","Corynebacterium diphtheriae"],a:3,e:"Group A beta-hemolytic streptococci fit the commonest bacterial cause of acute tonsillitis; characteristic presentation with fever, odynophagia, and tonsillar exudates. Cervical lymphadenopathy develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: bacterial invasion produces acute inflammation of palatine tonsils and surrounding pharyngeal mucosa symptomatically. Untreated infection may lead to suppurative or nonsuppurative complications.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus (option A), Klebsiella pneumoniae (option C), Pseudomonas aeruginosa (option B), and Corynebacterium diphtheriae (option E) occur less commonly. Therefore streptococci remain the predominant pathogen.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with fever, drooling, muffled voice, and unilateral tonsillar swelling with uvular deviation. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Acute epiglottitis","Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Vincent angina","Infectious mononucleosis"],a:1,e:"Peritonsillar abscess fits unilateral tonsillar swelling with uvular deviation and muffled \"hot potato\" voice; characteristic quinsy presentation. Trismus develops clinically in advanced cases.<br><br>Standard pathology: pus accumulates between tonsillar capsule and superior constrictor muscle following acute tonsillitis symptomatically. Swallowing becomes severely painful and difficult.<br><br>Acute epiglottitis (option A) primarily causes airway obstruction; retropharyngeal abscess (option C) affects posterior pharyngeal wall; Vincent angina (option D) causes ulceration; infectious mononucleosis (option E) presents bilaterally. Therefore findings strongly indicate peritonsillar abscess.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The characteristic membrane in diphtheria is:",o:["Easily removable white membrane","Thin transparent plaque","Yellow fungal patch","Thick gray adherent membrane","Hemorrhagic vesicle"],a:3,e:"Thick gray adherent membrane fits classical diphtheria; characteristic pseudomembrane firmly attached to inflamed mucosa. Bleeding occurs clinically on attempted removal.<br><br>Standard pathology: exotoxin-producing Corynebacterium diphtheriae causes necrosis and fibrinous exudate formation symptomatically. Airway compromise may develop in severe infections.<br><br>Easily removable white membrane (option A) suggests candidiasis; transparent plaque (option B) lacks specificity; fungal patch (option C) indicates oral thrush; hemorrhagic vesicle (option E) is unrelated. Therefore adherent gray membrane characterizes diphtheria.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Oral thrush is most commonly caused by:",o:["Candida albicans","Aspergillus fumigatus","Streptococcus pyogenes","Herpes simplex virus","Fusobacterium species"],a:0,e:"Candida albicans fits the commonest cause of oral thrush; characteristic opportunistic fungal infection producing white curd-like plaques. Immunocompromised patients develop clinically frequent disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: fungal overgrowth occurs after immune suppression, diabetes, or prolonged antibiotic therapy symptomatically. Lesions leave erythematous mucosa after scraping.<br><br>Aspergillus fumigatus (option B) affects respiratory tract mainly; Streptococcus pyogenes (option C) causes tonsillitis; herpes simplex virus (option D) causes vesicles; Fusobacterium species (option E) contribute Vincent angina. Therefore Candida commonly causes oral thrush.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe odynophagia, foul breath, and punched-out ulcers over gingiva most likely has:",o:["Herpangina","Aphthous ulcer","Vincent angina","Oral candidiasis","Diphtheria"],a:2,e:"Vincent angina fits foul breath with painful ulcerative gingival lesions; characteristic acute necrotizing ulcerative gingivitis presentation. Bleeding gums develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: fusospirochetal infection produces necrosis of interdental papillae and gingival mucosa symptomatically. Poor oral hygiene strongly predisposes disease.<br><br>Herpangina (option A) causes posterior oral vesicles; aphthous ulcer (option B) remains localized; oral candidiasis (option D) forms white plaques; diphtheria (option E) forms adherent membranes. Therefore ulcerative fetid gingivitis indicates Vincent infection.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common deep neck infection arising from dental infection is:",o:["Retropharyngeal abscess","Ludwig angina","Peritonsillar abscess","Parapharyngeal abscess","Epiglottitis"],a:1,e:"Ludwig angina fits the commonest deep neck infection arising from odontogenic infection; characteristic rapidly spreading cellulitis of submandibular spaces. Airway compromise develops clinically urgently.<br><br>Standard pathology: infection spreads bilaterally through fascial planes beneath the tongue causing floor of mouth elevation symptomatically. Prompt treatment remains essential.<br><br>Retropharyngeal abscess (option A) commonly follows upper respiratory infection; peritonsillar abscess (option C) complicates tonsillitis; parapharyngeal abscess (option D) lies laterally; epiglottitis (option E) affects supraglottic airway. Therefore dental infection frequently causes Ludwig angina.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient presents with painful white plaques over tongue and buccal mucosa that bleed on scraping. The diagnosis is:",o:["Leukoplakia","Diphtheria","Oral candidiasis","Oral lichen planus","Herpes stomatitis"],a:2,e:"Oral candidiasis fits painful removable white plaques with underlying erythema in diabetic patients; characteristic opportunistic fungal infection. Burning sensation develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: Candida overgrowth follows altered immunity and glucose-rich oral environments symptomatically. Lesions typically bleed slightly after scraping.<br><br>Leukoplakia (option A) cannot be scraped off; diphtheria (option B) forms gray membranes; oral lichen planus (option D) forms reticular lesions; herpes stomatitis (option E) produces vesicles. Therefore findings strongly suggest candidiasis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The primary causative virus of herpetic gingivostomatitis is:",o:["Epstein-Barr virus","Cytomegalovirus","Coxsackie virus","Herpes simplex virus type 1","Varicella-zoster virus"],a:3,e:"Herpes simplex virus type 1 fits the common cause of acute herpetic gingivostomatitis; characteristic painful vesicular oral lesions in children. Fever develops clinically before ulceration.<br><br>Standard pathology: viral infection causes epithelial cell destruction and vesicle formation throughout oral mucosa symptomatically. Primary infection may be severe.<br><br>Epstein-Barr virus (option A) causes mononucleosis; cytomegalovirus (option B) affects immunocompromised hosts; Coxsackie virus (option C) causes herpangina; varicella-zoster virus (option E) causes shingles. Therefore HSV-1 predominantly causes gingivostomatitis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with fever, trismus, drooling, and bilateral submandibular swelling after molar tooth infection. The diagnosis is:",o:["Retropharyngeal abscess","Infectious mononucleosis","Acute tonsillitis","Ludwig angina","Vincent angina"],a:3,e:"Ludwig angina fits bilateral submandibular swelling with trismus and drooling after dental infection; characteristic rapidly progressive cellulitis. Tongue elevation develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: infection spreads through submandibular and sublingual fascial spaces causing edema and airway compromise symptomatically. Emergency management becomes necessary.<br><br>Retropharyngeal abscess (option A) affects posterior pharynx; acute tonsillitis (option C) involves tonsils; infectious mononucleosis (option B) causes generalized lymphadenopathy; Vincent angina (option E) causes gingival ulceration. Therefore odontogenic swelling suggests Ludwig angina.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The hallmark feature of infectious mononucleosis is:",o:["Membranous pharyngitis with hepatosplenomegaly","Oral candidiasis","Bilateral vocal cord palsy","Nasal obstruction only","Facial cellulitis"],a:0,e:"Membranous pharyngitis with hepatosplenomegaly fits infectious mononucleosis; characteristic Epstein-Barr virus presentation in adolescents. Cervical lymphadenopathy develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard pathology: viral lymphoproliferation produces systemic symptoms and atypical lymphocytosis symptomatically. Tonsillar enlargement may mimic bacterial tonsillitis.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option B) represents fungal infection; bilateral vocal cord palsy (option C) affects laryngeal nerves; nasal obstruction (option D) lacks systemic findings; facial cellulitis (option E) involves soft tissue infection. Therefore hepatosplenomegaly strongly suggests mononucleosis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common complication of acute tonsillitis is:",o:["Meningitis","Peritonsillar abscess","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Facial palsy","Retinal detachment"],a:1,e:"Peritonsillar abscess fits the most common complication of acute tonsillitis; characteristic suppurative spread around tonsillar capsule. Severe odynophagia develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Standard pathology: infection extends into peritonsillar space producing localized pus collection and edema symptomatically. Speech becomes muffled in advanced cases.<br><br>Meningitis (option A) occurs rarely; cavernous sinus thrombosis (option C) follows facial infections; facial palsy (option D) affects facial nerve; retinal detachment (option E) is unrelated. Therefore quinsy remains the commonest complication.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with fever and vesicular lesions over soft palate and tonsillar pillars most likely has:",o:["Oral candidiasis","Ludwig angina","Diphtheria","Herpangina","Aphthous stomatitis"],a:3,e:"Herpangina fits vesicular lesions involving soft palate and tonsillar pillars in febrile children; characteristic Coxsackie virus infection. Painful swallowing develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: viral infection produces vesicles and ulcers in posterior oral cavity structures symptomatically. Disease usually resolves spontaneously.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option A) forms white plaques; diphtheria (option C) forms adherent membrane; Ludwig angina (option B) causes cellulitis; aphthous stomatitis (option E) forms isolated ulcers. Therefore posterior oral vesicles suggest herpangina.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common bacterial cause of Ludwig angina originates from infection of the:",o:["Upper incisors","Lower second and third molars","Upper canines","Premolars only","Upper wisdom tooth only"],a:1,e:"Lower second and third molars fit the common dental source of Ludwig angina; characteristic spread into submandibular spaces through root anatomy. Airway obstruction develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Standard anatomy: molar roots extend below mylohyoid attachment permitting direct fascial spread of infection symptomatically. Bilateral involvement commonly occurs.<br><br>Upper incisors (option A), upper canines (option C), premolars only (option D), and upper wisdom tooth only (option E) less commonly produce this infection. Therefore lower molars represent the major source.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe sore throat with deviation of uvula to the opposite side. Which condition is most likely?",o:["Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Oral candidiasis","Diphtheria","Leukoplakia"],a:0,e:"Peritonsillar abscess fits severe sore throat with contralateral uvular deviation; characteristic unilateral pus collection near tonsil. Trismus develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: inflammatory edema and abscess formation displace soft palate and uvula away from affected side symptomatically. Swallowing becomes markedly painful.<br><br>Retropharyngeal abscess (option B) produces posterior wall bulging; oral candidiasis (option C) forms plaques; diphtheria (option D) forms membranes; leukoplakia (option E) remains noninfective. Therefore uvular deviation strongly indicates peritonsillar abscess.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The causative organism of diphtheria produces disease mainly through:",o:["Endotoxin production","Direct tissue invasion only","Exotoxin production","Granuloma formation","Immune complex deposition"],a:2,e:"Exotoxin production fits the pathogenic mechanism of diphtheria; characteristic inhibition of cellular protein synthesis. Myocarditis develops clinically in severe systemic disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: Corynebacterium diphtheriae exotoxin causes local necrosis and systemic toxic complications symptomatically. Prompt antitoxin therapy remains essential.<br><br>Endotoxin production (option A) characterizes gram-negative bacteria; direct tissue invasion only (option B) is insufficient; granuloma formation (option D) suggests chronic infection; immune complex deposition (option E) occurs differently. Therefore exotoxin mediates diphtheria manifestations.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with HIV develops painful oral white lesions that cannot be scraped off. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Oral candidiasis","Hairy leukoplakia","Vincent angina","Diphtheria","Acute tonsillitis"],a:1,e:"Hairy leukoplakia fits nonremovable white oral lesions in HIV patients; characteristic Epstein-Barr virus-associated mucosal lesion. Lateral tongue involvement develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: epithelial hyperplasia with viral changes produces corrugated white plaques symptomatically. Lesions differ from candidiasis by adherence.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option A) can be scraped off; Vincent angina (option C) causes ulcerative gingivitis; diphtheria (option D) forms gray membranes; acute tonsillitis (option E) affects tonsils. Therefore adherent white plaques suggest hairy leukoplakia.<br><br><em>(Recall and First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous complication of Ludwig angina is:",o:["Hearing loss","Orbital cellulitis","Facial paralysis","Airway obstruction","Epistaxis"],a:3,e:"Airway obstruction fits the most dangerous complication of Ludwig angina; characteristic tongue elevation and floor of mouth edema. Respiratory distress develops clinically urgently.<br><br>Standard pathology: rapidly spreading cellulitis narrows upper airway through soft tissue swelling symptomatically. Emergency airway management may become lifesaving.<br><br>Hearing loss (option A), facial paralysis (option C), orbital cellulitis (option B), and epistaxis (option E) are unrelated major complications. Therefore airway compromise represents the greatest threat.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with pseudomembrane over tonsils and bull neck appearance. The diagnosis is:",o:["Infectious mononucleosis","Acute follicular tonsillitis","Ludwig angina","Herpangina","Diphtheria"],a:4,e:"Diphtheria fits pseudomembrane formation with characteristic bull neck swelling; hallmark toxic bacterial infection presentation. Cervical edema develops clinically in severe cases.<br><br>Standard pathology: exotoxin-mediated inflammation produces adherent membranes and regional lymphadenopathy symptomatically. Systemic cardiac complications may follow.<br><br>Infectious mononucleosis (option A) causes generalized lymphadenopathy; follicular tonsillitis (option B) forms exudates; herpangina (option D) causes vesicles; Ludwig angina (option C) affects submandibular spaces. Therefore bull neck strongly suggests diphtheria.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of aphthous ulceration is the:",o:["Buccal mucosa","Hard palate","Gingiva only","Dorsum of tongue","Tonsillar fossa"],a:0,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest site of aphthous ulceration; characteristic painful recurrent shallow oral ulcers. Eating becomes clinically uncomfortable during attacks.<br><br>Standard pathology: localized mucosal immune-mediated ulceration affects nonkeratinized oral mucosa symptomatically. Lesions usually heal spontaneously without scarring.<br><br>Hard palate (option B) and dorsum of tongue (option D) are keratinized; gingiva only (option C) is less common; tonsillar fossa (option E) belongs oropharynx. Therefore buccal mucosa commonly develops aphthous ulcers.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral sore throat, neck stiffness, and posterior pharyngeal wall bulge most likely has:",o:["Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Oral candidiasis","Herpangina","Vincent angina"],a:1,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess fits posterior pharyngeal wall swelling with neck stiffness and severe throat pain; characteristic deep neck space infection. Dysphagia develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard pathology: suppuration occurs within retropharyngeal lymph nodes and fascial spaces symptomatically. Airway obstruction may complicate severe cases.<br><br>Peritonsillar abscess (option A) displaces uvula; oral candidiasis (option C) forms plaques; herpangina (option D) forms vesicles; Vincent angina (option E) causes gingival ulcers. Therefore posterior wall bulging suggests retropharyngeal abscess.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common fungal infection of oral cavity is:",o:["Aspergillosis","Histoplasmosis","Oral candidiasis","Mucormycosis","Blastomycosis"],a:2,e:"Oral candidiasis fits the commonest fungal infection affecting the oral cavity; characteristic white removable plaques over oral mucosa. Immunocompromised patients are clinically predisposed frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: Candida overgrowth follows antibiotic therapy, diabetes, or immunosuppression symptomatically. Burning discomfort and erythema commonly accompany lesions.<br><br>Aspergillosis (option A), histoplasmosis (option B), mucormycosis (option D), and blastomycosis (option E) involve oral cavity far less commonly. Therefore candidiasis predominates among oral fungal infections.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent oral ulcers, genital ulcers, and uveitis most likely has:",o:["Herpangina","Diphtheria","Vincent angina","Behçet disease","Ludwig angina"],a:3,e:"Behçet disease fits recurrent oral ulcers associated with genital ulcers and uveitis; characteristic multisystem inflammatory vasculitic disorder. Painful mucosal lesions develop clinically repeatedly.<br><br>Standard pathology: immune-mediated vascular inflammation affects oral, ocular, and genital tissues symptomatically. Neurological and vascular complications may occur additionally.<br><br>Herpangina (option A) is viral; Vincent angina (option C) affects gingiva; diphtheria (option B) forms membranes; Ludwig angina (option E) causes cellulitis. Therefore recurrent multisystem ulceration suggests Behçet disease.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The treatment of choice for peritonsillar abscess includes:",o:["Observation only","Needle aspiration or incision and drainage","Oral antifungals only","Radiation therapy","Intranasal steroids"],a:1,e:"Needle aspiration or incision and drainage fit definitive treatment of peritonsillar abscess; characteristic management relieving pus collection and pressure. Antibiotics accompany clinically standard therapy.<br><br>Standard treatment removes purulent material while controlling infection and preventing airway complications symptomatically. Early intervention improves pain and swallowing rapidly.<br><br>Observation only (option A) risks progression; oral antifungals (option C) treat candidiasis; radiation therapy (option D) treats malignancy; intranasal steroids (option E) affect rhinitis. Therefore drainage remains the treatment of choice.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with painful grouped vesicles over lips and oral mucosa following fever. The diagnosis is:",o:["Herpetic stomatitis","Aphthous stomatitis","Oral candidiasis","Leukoplakia","Diphtheria"],a:0,e:"Herpetic stomatitis fits painful grouped oral vesicles appearing after febrile illness; characteristic herpes simplex virus infection presentation. Ulceration follows clinically after vesicle rupture.<br><br>Standard pathology: viral cytopathic effect causes epithelial destruction and vesicular lesion formation symptomatically. Recurrences may occur with stress or immunosuppression.<br><br>Aphthous stomatitis (option B) forms isolated ulcers; oral candidiasis (option C) produces plaques; leukoplakia (option D) remains white adherent lesion; diphtheria (option E) forms membranes. Therefore grouped vesicles suggest herpetic stomatitis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest indication for tonsillectomy in recurrent tonsillitis is:",o:["One attack yearly","Five or more attacks yearly","Mild halitosis only","Allergic rhinitis","Single sore throat episode"],a:1,e:"Five or more attacks yearly fit the common indication for tonsillectomy in recurrent tonsillitis; characteristic criterion used in clinical decision making. Quality of life improves clinically after surgery.<br><br>Standard management recommends surgery when recurrent infections significantly impair normal activities and antibiotic requirements symptomatically. Careful patient selection remains important.<br><br>One attack yearly (option A) and single sore throat episode (option E) are insufficient; mild halitosis only (option C) rarely requires surgery; allergic rhinitis (option D) does not indicate tonsillectomy. Therefore frequent recurrent infections justify operative management.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cause of recurrent painful oral ulcers is:",o:["Oral candidiasis","Aphthous stomatitis","Syphilis","Tuberculosis","Leukoplakia"],a:1,e:"Aphthous stomatitis fits the commonest cause of recurrent painful oral ulcers; characteristic shallow round lesions with erythematous margins. Eating becomes clinically uncomfortable during episodes.<br><br>Standard pathology: immune-mediated mucosal inflammation produces recurrent ulceration over nonkeratinized oral surfaces symptomatically. Stress and nutritional deficiencies may precipitate attacks.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option A) forms white plaques; syphilis (option C) causes painless chancre; tuberculosis (option D) produces chronic ulcers; leukoplakia (option E) is premalignant white lesion. Therefore aphthous stomatitis predominates among recurrent ulcers.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of aphthous ulcers is the:",o:["Hard palate","Attached gingiva","Dorsum of tongue","Buccal mucosa","Tonsillar fossa"],a:3,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest site of aphthous ulcers; characteristic involvement of nonkeratinized oral mucosa. Pain during mastication develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: superficial immune-mediated ulceration affects movable oral mucosal surfaces symptomatically. Lesions usually heal without scarring in minor aphthae.<br><br>Hard palate (option A) and dorsum of tongue (option C) are keratinized; attached gingiva (option B) is less commonly involved; tonsillar fossa (option E) belongs oropharynx. Therefore buccal mucosa remains the usual location.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless indurated ulcer over the tongue with rolled margins should be considered:",o:["Aphthous ulcer","Tuberculous ulcer","Herpetic ulcer","Traumatic ulcer","Squamous cell carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits painless indurated oral ulcers with rolled margins; characteristic malignant presentation involving tongue or buccal mucosa. Cervical metastasis develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic epithelial dysplasia progresses toward invasive squamous malignancy producing ulcerative destructive lesions symptomatically. Tobacco exposure strongly predisposes disease.<br><br>Aphthous ulcer (option A) remains painful; tuberculous ulcer (option B) is undermined; traumatic ulcer (option D) heals after irritation removal; herpetic ulcer (option C) follows vesicles. Therefore induration strongly suggests carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common organism associated with oral candidiasis is:",o:["Candida albicans","Aspergillus species","Fusobacterium species","Herpes simplex virus","Treponema pallidum"],a:0,e:"Candida albicans fits the most common fungal cause of oral ulcerative and pseudomembranous lesions; characteristic opportunistic pathogen in immunocompromised states. Burning discomfort develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: fungal overgrowth follows antibiotic use, diabetes, or immunosuppression producing mucosal inflammation symptomatically. White plaques may leave raw ulcers after scraping.<br><br>Aspergillus species (option B) mainly affect respiratory tract; Fusobacterium species (option C) cause Vincent angina; herpes simplex virus (option D) causes vesicles; Treponema pallidum (option E) causes syphilis. Therefore Candida predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent oral ulcers, genital ulcers, and uveitis most likely has:",o:["Behçet disease","Syphilis","Tuberculosis","Diphtheria","Ludwig angina"],a:0,e:"Behçet disease fits recurrent oral ulcers associated with genital ulceration and uveitis; characteristic multisystem vasculitic disorder. Painful mucosal lesions recur clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: immune-mediated vascular inflammation affects oral, ocular, and genital tissues symptomatically. Neurological and vascular complications may occur additionally.<br><br>Syphilis (option B) produces painless chancre; tuberculosis (option C) forms chronic ulcers; diphtheria (option D) forms pseudomembrane; Ludwig angina (option E) causes cellulitis. Therefore recurrent multisystem ulceration suggests Behçet disease.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The characteristic ulcer of primary syphilis is:",o:["Painful irregular ulcer","Multiple vesicular ulcer","Painless indurated chancre","Necrotic gingival ulcer","Fungating ulcer"],a:2,e:"Painless indurated chancre fits primary syphilitic oral ulcers; characteristic firm lesion with clean base and raised edges. Regional lymphadenopathy develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: Treponema pallidum infection produces localized plasma cell-rich inflammation and vascular changes symptomatically. Healing may occur spontaneously despite persistent infection.<br><br>Painful irregular ulcer (option A) suggests trauma or aphthous disease; vesicular ulcers (option B) indicate herpes infection; necrotic gingival ulcer (option D) occurs in Vincent angina; fungating ulcer (option E) suggests malignancy. Therefore chancre remains characteristic.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A chronic painful ulcer with undermined edges on tongue should raise suspicion for:",o:["Leukoplakia","Tuberculosis","Aphthous ulcer","Herpangina","Oral candidiasis"],a:1,e:"Tuberculosis fits chronic painful ulcers with undermined edges involving the tongue; characteristic secondary oral tuberculous lesion appearance. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: granulomatous inflammation with caseation necrosis produces chronic ulcerative mucosal destruction symptomatically. Pulmonary tuberculosis commonly coexists.<br><br>Leukoplakia (option A) forms white plaques; aphthous ulcer (option C) heals rapidly; herpangina (option D) causes vesicles; oral candidiasis (option E) produces plaques. Therefore undermined chronic ulcers suggest tuberculosis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of oral cancer-related ulceration is the:",o:["Hard palate","Floor of mouth","Upper lip","Soft palate","Buccal mucosa"],a:4,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest site of oral cancer ulceration in South Asian populations; characteristic association with tobacco and betel nut chewing. Nonhealing ulcers develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic carcinogenic exposure induces progressive epithelial dysplasia and invasive squamous carcinoma symptomatically. Cervical nodal spread occurs early.<br><br>Hard palate (option A), floor of mouth (option B), soft palate (option D), and upper lip (option C) are less frequently involved locally. Therefore buccal mucosa remains most commonly affected.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with fever and multiple painful oral ulcers preceded by vesicles. The likely diagnosis is:",o:["Aphthous stomatitis","Tuberculous ulcer","Syphilitic ulcer","Herpetic stomatitis","Traumatic ulcer"],a:3,e:"Herpetic stomatitis fits painful ulcers preceded by vesicle formation and fever; characteristic herpes simplex virus infection presentation. Cervical lymphadenopathy develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Standard pathology: viral cytopathic injury causes vesicles that rupture into shallow painful ulcers symptomatically. Primary infections are often severe in children.<br><br>Aphthous stomatitis (option A) lacks vesicles; syphilitic ulcer (option C) is painless; tuberculous ulcer (option B) remains chronic; traumatic ulcer (option E) follows local injury. Therefore vesicle-associated ulcers indicate herpes infection.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A solitary ulcer over lateral border of tongue persisting more than three weeks should be:",o:["Observed only","Treated with antifungals","Biopsied","Managed with saline gargles only","Ignored if painless"],a:2,e:"Biopsy fits persistent solitary ulcers over the lateral tongue border; characteristic concern for squamous cell carcinoma. Early diagnosis improves clinically overall prognosis significantly.<br><br>Standard oncology principles require histopathologic confirmation for chronic nonhealing oral ulcers symptomatically. Delay in evaluation increases metastatic risk.<br><br>Observation only (option A), antifungals (option B), and saline gargles (option D) may postpone diagnosis; painless lesions (option E) still require assessment. Therefore persistent tongue ulcers demand biopsy.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common predisposing factor for traumatic oral ulcers is:",o:["Viral infection","Sharp tooth edge","Fungal infection","Syphilis","Tuberculosis"],a:1,e:"Sharp tooth edges fit the commonest cause of traumatic oral ulcers; characteristic repeated mechanical irritation of mucosal surfaces. Pain develops clinically during mastication.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic friction causes epithelial breakdown and localized inflammatory ulceration symptomatically. Removal of the irritant usually promotes healing rapidly.<br><br>Viral infection (option A), fungal infection (option C), syphilis (option D), and tuberculosis (option E) produce infectious ulcers rather than traumatic lesions. Therefore dental irritation commonly causes traumatic ulcers.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with HIV presents with nonhealing oral ulcers and white adherent plaques over the tongue. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Hairy leukoplakia","Aphthous ulcer","Herpangina","Diphtheria","Traumatic ulcer"],a:0,e:"Hairy leukoplakia fits adherent white oral lesions in immunocompromised HIV patients; characteristic Epstein-Barr virus-associated mucosal lesion. Lateral tongue involvement occurs clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: epithelial hyperplasia and viral cytopathic changes produce corrugated white plaques symptomatically. Lesions cannot be scraped away.<br><br>Aphthous ulcers (option B) are painful erosions; herpangina (option C) forms vesicles; diphtheria (option D) forms membranes; traumatic ulcers (option E) result from injury. Therefore adherent white lesions suggest hairy leukoplakia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral ulcer associated with Vincent angina is typically:",o:["Painless and indurated","Vesicular","Fungating","Covered with curd-like plaques","Necrotic and foul smelling"],a:4,e:"Necrotic foul-smelling ulcers fit Vincent angina; characteristic acute necrotizing ulcerative gingivitis caused by fusospirochetal infection. Gingival bleeding develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: bacterial invasion produces tissue necrosis involving interdental papillae and gingival mucosa symptomatically. Poor oral hygiene strongly predisposes disease.<br><br>Painless indurated ulcers (option A) suggest syphilis or carcinoma; vesicular lesions (option B) indicate herpes infection; curd-like plaques (option D) occur in candidiasis; fungating ulcers (option C) suggest malignancy. Therefore foul necrotic ulcers indicate Vincent angina.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Minor aphthous ulcers usually heal within:",o:["24 hours","3-5 days","7-14 days","One month","Six months"],a:2,e:"Seven to fourteen days fit the usual healing period of minor aphthous ulcers; characteristic spontaneous recovery without scar formation. Recurrences develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: superficial immune-mediated mucosal ulceration resolves after inflammatory healing processes symptomatically. Episodes may recur during stress or nutritional deficiency.<br><br>Twenty-four hours (option A) is too short; three to five days (option B) remains uncommon; one month (option D) and six months (option E) suggest chronic pathology. Therefore minor aphthae usually heal within two weeks.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with recurrent oral ulcers and iron deficiency anemia. The likely association is:",o:["Aphthous stomatitis","Tuberculosis","Diphtheria","Syphilis","Herpangina"],a:0,e:"Aphthous stomatitis fits recurrent oral ulcers associated with iron deficiency anemia; characteristic nutritional deficiency correlation. Painful eating develops clinically repeatedly.<br><br>Standard pathology: deficiencies of iron, folate, or vitamin B12 predispose immune-mediated mucosal ulceration symptomatically. Correction of deficiencies often reduces recurrence frequency.<br><br>Tuberculosis (option B), diphtheria (option C), syphilis (option D), and herpangina (option E) do not strongly associate with iron deficiency. Therefore recurrent ulcers commonly suggest aphthous disease.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site for traumatic ulcer from ill-fitting dentures is the:",o:["Gingivobuccal sulcus","Hard palate","Floor of mouth","Soft palate","Tonsillar pillar"],a:0,e:"Gingivobuccal sulcus fits the commonest location for denture-related traumatic ulcers; characteristic repeated mucosal friction site. Pain worsens clinically during chewing.<br><br>Standard pathology: poorly fitting dentures repeatedly traumatize oral mucosa causing localized inflammatory ulceration symptomatically. Removal or adjustment usually promotes healing.<br><br>Hard palate (option B), floor of mouth (option C), soft palate (option D), and tonsillar pillar (option E) are less frequently traumatized by dentures. Therefore gingivobuccal sulcus commonly ulcerates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A large aphthous ulcer healing with scarring is classified as:",o:["Minor aphthous ulcer","Major aphthous ulcer","Herpetiform ulcer","Syphilitic ulcer","Tuberculous ulcer"],a:1,e:"Major aphthous ulcers fit large painful lesions healing with scar formation; characteristic severe form of recurrent aphthous stomatitis. Swallowing becomes clinically difficult occasionally.<br><br>Standard pathology: deeper mucosal ulceration produces prolonged healing and fibrosis symptomatically. Lesions may persist for several weeks.<br><br>Minor aphthous ulcers (option A) heal without scars; herpetiform ulcers (option C) are multiple tiny ulcers; syphilitic ulcers (option D) are painless chancres; tuberculous ulcers (option E) are chronic undermined lesions. Therefore scarring indicates major aphthae.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral lesion classically associated with Crohn disease is:",o:["Aphthous-like ulceration","Gray pseudomembrane","Hairy leukoplakia","Bullous lesion only","Black eschar"],a:0,e:"Aphthous-like ulceration fits the characteristic oral manifestation of Crohn disease; recurrent painful lesions occur clinically during active intestinal disease. Lip swelling may accompany ulcers.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic granulomatous inflammation affects gastrointestinal and oral mucosal tissues symptomatically. Nutritional deficiencies additionally worsen ulcer recurrence.<br><br>Gray pseudomembrane (option B) suggests diphtheria; hairy leukoplakia (option C) associates HIV infection; isolated bullous lesions (option D) are nonspecific; black eschar (option E) suggests mucormycosis. Therefore aphthous-type ulcers commonly occur in Crohn disease.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A nonhealing ulcer on lateral tongue in a chronic smoker is most suspicious for:",o:["Tuberculosis","Syphilis","Aphthous ulcer","Herpetic ulcer","Squamous cell carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits chronic nonhealing tongue ulcers in smokers; characteristic malignant oral lesion associated with tobacco exposure. Cervical nodal spread develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic carcinogenic exposure causes epithelial dysplasia progressing toward invasive carcinoma symptomatically. Lesions become indurated with rolled edges.<br><br>Tuberculosis (option A) produces undermined ulcers; syphilis (option B) causes painless chancre; herpetic ulcers (option D) follow vesicles; aphthous ulcers (option C) heal spontaneously. Therefore persistent smoker-associated ulcers strongly suggest carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Herpetiform aphthous ulcers are characterized by:",o:["Single large ulcer only","Multiple tiny painful ulcers","Painless white plaque","Thick gray membrane","Fungating lesion"],a:1,e:"Multiple tiny painful ulcers fit herpetiform aphthous stomatitis; characteristic clusters resembling herpes lesions without viral etiology. Burning pain develops clinically significantly.<br><br>Standard pathology: numerous small superficial aphthous ulcers occur over oral mucosa symptomatically. Lesions may merge into larger erosive areas.<br><br>Single large ulcers (option A) suggest major aphthae; painless white plaques (option C) suggest leukoplakia; gray membrane (option D) occurs in diphtheria; fungating lesions (option E) indicate malignancy. Therefore clustered tiny ulcers characterize herpetiform aphthae.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important investigation for a chronic suspicious oral ulcer is:",o:["Blood glucose","FNAC only","Incisional biopsy","ESR","Mantoux test"],a:2,e:"Incisional biopsy fits the most important investigation for chronic suspicious oral ulcers; characteristic definitive diagnostic method for malignancy exclusion. Early detection improves clinically prognosis significantly.<br><br>Standard pathology evaluation permits histologic assessment of dysplasia, carcinoma, or granulomatous disease symptomatically. Persistent ulcers always require tissue diagnosis.<br><br>Blood glucose (option A), ESR (option D), and Mantoux test (option E) provide supportive information only; FNAC alone (option B) inadequately assesses surface mucosal lesions. Therefore incisional biopsy remains essential.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with oral ulcers and target lesions over skin most likely has:",o:["Erythema multiforme","Oral candidiasis","Vincent angina","Syphilis","Leukoplakia"],a:0,e:"Erythema multiforme fits oral ulceration associated with target skin lesions; characteristic hypersensitivity reaction often triggered by infections or drugs. Painful erosions develop clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard pathology: immune-mediated epithelial injury affects mucocutaneous surfaces symptomatically. Severe forms may involve widespread mucosal destruction.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option B) forms plaques; Vincent angina (option C) affects gingiva; syphilis (option D) causes chancre; leukoplakia (option E) forms white lesions. Therefore target lesions strongly suggest erythema multiforme.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cause of oral ulcers in chemotherapy patients is:",o:["Syphilis","Diphtheria","Tuberculosis","Mucositis","Vincent angina"],a:3,e:"Mucositis fits the commonest cause of oral ulceration during chemotherapy; characteristic toxic injury to rapidly dividing oral epithelium. Severe pain develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: cytotoxic drugs damage mucosal epithelial turnover leading to ulceration and inflammation symptomatically. Secondary infections may complicate lesions additionally.<br><br>Syphilis (option A), tuberculosis (option C), diphtheria (option B), and Vincent angina (option E) are unrelated infectious disorders. Therefore chemotherapy commonly causes mucositis-related ulcers.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A painful ulcer with erythematous halo and yellow floor is characteristic of:",o:["Aphthous ulcer","Syphilitic chancre","Tuberculous ulcer","Carcinomatous ulcer","Leukoplakia"],a:0,e:"Aphthous ulcer fits painful shallow lesions with yellow floor and surrounding erythematous halo; characteristic recurrent stomatitis presentation. Eating acidic food worsens clinically discomfort.<br><br>Standard pathology: localized immune-mediated mucosal inflammation produces superficial ulceration symptomatically. Minor lesions usually heal spontaneously within two weeks.<br><br>Syphilitic chancre (option B) is painless; tuberculous ulcers (option C) are undermined; carcinomatous ulcers (option D) are indurated; leukoplakia (option E) forms white plaques. Therefore classic haloed ulcers suggest aphthous disease.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of squamous cell carcinoma ulcer in oral cavity is the:",o:["Buccal mucosa","Hard palate","Upper lip","Gingiva","Soft palate"],a:0,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest oral site of squamous carcinoma ulceration in high-risk populations; characteristic association with tobacco chewing. Persistent ulcers develop clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: repeated carcinogenic exposure induces epithelial dysplasia and malignant transformation symptomatically. Cervical lymph node metastasis may occur early.<br><br>Hard palate (option B), upper lip (option C), gingiva (option D), and soft palate (option E) are comparatively less common locations. Therefore buccal mucosa remains the predominant site.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant tumor of the oral cavity is:",o:["Squamous cell carcinoma","Adenocarcinoma","Melanoma","Fibrosarcoma","Lymphoma"],a:0,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits the commonest malignant oral cavity tumor; characteristic association with tobacco, betel nut, and alcohol exposure. Nonhealing ulcers develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic epithelial dysplasia progresses toward invasive squamous malignancy involving oral mucosa symptomatically. Cervical lymph node metastasis occurs relatively early.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma (option B) arises from glandular tissue; melanoma (option C) is uncommon orally; fibrosarcoma (option D) arises from connective tissue; lymphoma (option E) involves lymphoid structures. Therefore squamous carcinoma predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of oral cavity carcinoma in South Asian populations is the:",o:["Hard palate","Floor of mouth","Soft palate","Tongue dorsum","Buccal mucosa"],a:4,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest site of oral carcinoma in South Asian populations; characteristic relation with betel nut and tobacco chewing habits. Ulcerative lesions develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: repeated carcinogenic exposure induces epithelial dysplasia and invasive malignant transformation symptomatically. Cervical nodal metastasis may occur early.<br><br>Hard palate (option A), floor of mouth (option B), tongue dorsum (option D), and soft palate (option C) are less frequently involved regionally. Therefore buccal mucosa remains the predominant site.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important premalignant lesion of oral cavity is:",o:["Aphthous ulcer","Leukoplakia","Oral candidiasis","Herpetic stomatitis","Diphtheria"],a:1,e:"Leukoplakia fits the most important premalignant lesion of the oral cavity; characteristic persistent white patch not attributable to other causes. Malignant transformation develops clinically in some lesions.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic epithelial hyperplasia and dysplasia occur secondary to carcinogenic exposure symptomatically. Histologic grading guides prognosis and treatment.<br><br>Aphthous ulcer (option A) is inflammatory; oral candidiasis (option C) is fungal; herpetic stomatitis (option D) is viral; diphtheria (option E) is bacterial. Therefore leukoplakia carries significant premalignant potential.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with a nonhealing ulcer on the lateral border of tongue most likely has:",o:["Oral candidiasis","Aphthous ulcer","Squamous cell carcinoma","Herpangina","Vincent angina"],a:2,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits nonhealing ulcers involving the lateral tongue border; characteristic high-risk malignant oral lesion. Induration develops clinically during disease progression.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic carcinogenic exposure causes epithelial dysplasia followed by invasive squamous malignancy symptomatically. Cervical metastasis frequently accompanies tongue cancers.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option A) forms removable plaques; aphthous ulcers (option B) heal rapidly; herpangina (option D) produces vesicles; Vincent angina (option E) causes gingival necrosis. Therefore persistent tongue ulcers strongly suggest carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common benign tumor of oral cavity is:",o:["Hemangioma","Fibroma","Papilloma","Osteoma","Lipoma"],a:1,e:"Fibroma fits the commonest benign tumor of the oral cavity; characteristic localized connective tissue overgrowth following chronic irritation. Slow enlargement develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: reactive fibroblastic proliferation produces smooth firm mucosal nodules symptomatically. Surgical excision usually remains curative.<br><br>Hemangioma (option A) is vascular; papilloma (option C) is epithelial; osteoma (option D) is bony; lipoma (option E) consists of adipose tissue. Therefore fibroma predominates among benign oral tumors.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The strongest etiological factor for oral cavity carcinoma is:",o:["Viral rhinitis","Chronic otitis media","Acute tonsillitis","Tobacco use","Allergic rhinitis"],a:3,e:"Tobacco use fits the strongest etiological factor for oral cavity carcinoma; characteristic association with smoking and chewing preparations. Chronic mucosal irritation develops clinically over years.<br><br>Standard pathology: carcinogens induce epithelial dysplasia and progressive genetic mutations leading to invasive malignancy symptomatically. Combined alcohol use further increases risk.<br><br>Viral rhinitis (option A), acute tonsillitis (option C), chronic otitis media (option B), and allergic rhinitis (option E) lack strong oncogenic association. Therefore tobacco remains the principal risk factor.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A cauliflower-like exophytic lesion in oral cavity is most suggestive of:",o:["Papilloma","Tuberculous ulcer","Aphthous ulcer","Syphilitic chancre","Fibrosarcoma"],a:0,e:"Papilloma fits cauliflower-like exophytic oral lesions; characteristic benign epithelial proliferation often associated with human papillomavirus infection. Slow growth develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: squamous epithelial hyperplasia forms papillary projections supported by fibrovascular cores symptomatically. Surgical excision is usually curative.<br><br>Tuberculous ulcers (option B) are undermined; aphthous ulcers (option C) are painful erosions; syphilitic chancres (option D) are indurated ulcers; fibrosarcoma (option E) is malignant connective tissue tumor. Therefore papilloma produces exophytic growth.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral cavity cancer with highest tendency for early metastasis is carcinoma of the:",o:["Hard palate","Buccal mucosa","Gingiva","Upper lip","Tongue"],a:4,e:"Tongue carcinoma fits the oral malignancy with highest tendency for early metastasis; characteristic rich lymphatic drainage of the tongue. Cervical nodal involvement develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Standard pathology: invasive malignant cells spread bilaterally through abundant lymphatic channels symptomatically. Prognosis worsens significantly with nodal disease.<br><br>Hard palate (option A), buccal mucosa (option B), upper lip (option D), and gingiva (option C) metastasize relatively later. Therefore tongue cancers show aggressive metastatic behavior.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Erythroplakia is clinically important because it:",o:["Is always infectious","Never undergoes malignant change","Occurs only in children","Represents fungal disease only","Has high malignant potential"],a:4,e:"Erythroplakia fits an oral lesion with particularly high malignant potential; characteristic red velvety mucosal patch frequently showing dysplasia. Biopsy becomes clinically mandatory.<br><br>Standard pathology: severe epithelial atypia and carcinoma in situ occur commonly within erythroplakic lesions symptomatically. Malignant transformation rates exceed leukoplakia.<br><br>Infectious origin (option A) is incorrect; absence of malignant change (option B) is false; fungal disease only (option D) lacks basis; childhood restriction (option C) is inaccurate. Therefore erythroplakia warrants urgent evaluation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A smoker presents with a persistent white patch over buccal mucosa that cannot be scraped off. The diagnosis is:",o:["Oral candidiasis","Leukoplakia","Aphthous ulcer","Diphtheria","Herpetic stomatitis"],a:1,e:"Leukoplakia fits persistent nonscrapable white oral patches in smokers; characteristic premalignant epithelial lesion associated with chronic irritation. Dysplastic transformation develops clinically in some cases.<br><br>Standard pathology: hyperkeratosis and epithelial atypia occur due to carcinogenic exposure symptomatically. Histologic examination guides further management.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option A) can be scraped away; aphthous ulcers (option C) are painful ulcers; diphtheria (option D) forms membranes; herpetic stomatitis (option E) produces vesicles. Therefore nonscrapable white plaques suggest leukoplakia.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest salivary gland tumor affecting minor salivary glands of oral cavity is:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Warthin tumor","Mucoepidermoid carcinoma","Acinic cell carcinoma","Hemangioma"],a:0,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma fits the commonest salivary gland tumor affecting oral minor salivary glands; characteristic painless slow-growing palatal mass. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>Standard pathology: mixed epithelial and stromal proliferation forms encapsulated salivary tumors symptomatically. Malignant transformation may occur rarely.<br><br>Warthin tumor (option B) mainly affects parotid gland; mucoepidermoid carcinoma (option C) is malignant; acinic cell carcinoma (option D) occurs less frequently; hemangioma (option E) is vascular. Therefore pleomorphic adenoma predominates.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site for verrucous carcinoma in oral cavity is the:",o:["Buccal mucosa","Hard palate","Tongue dorsum","Floor of mouth","Tonsillar pillar"],a:0,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest site for verrucous carcinoma; characteristic association with smokeless tobacco and betel nut chewing. Slow local enlargement develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: well-differentiated squamous proliferation produces warty exophytic growth with minimal metastatic tendency symptomatically. Local invasion remains significant.<br><br>Hard palate (option B), tongue dorsum (option C), floor of mouth (option D), and tonsillar pillar (option E) are less commonly involved. Therefore buccal mucosa frequently develops verrucous carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A bluish compressible lesion over oral mucosa that increases on crying is most likely:",o:["Fibroma","Hemangioma","Papilloma","Lipoma","Squamous carcinoma"],a:1,e:"Hemangioma fits bluish compressible oral lesions enlarging during crying or straining; characteristic benign vascular tumor presentation. Bleeding develops clinically after trauma occasionally.<br><br>Standard pathology: proliferation of vascular channels produces soft compressible lesions with increased venous filling symptomatically. Many regress spontaneously in childhood.<br><br>Fibroma (option A) is firm; papilloma (option C) is papillary; lipoma (option D) appears yellowish; squamous carcinoma (option E) ulcerates and indurates. Therefore vascular compressibility strongly suggests hemangioma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral cavity lesion most strongly associated with HPV infection is:",o:["Fibroma","Traumatic ulcer","Leukoplakia","Papilloma","Ranula"],a:3,e:"Papilloma fits the oral lesion most strongly associated with human papillomavirus infection; characteristic exophytic papillary mucosal growth. Small painless masses develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: HPV-induced epithelial hyperplasia forms finger-like mucosal projections supported by fibrovascular cores symptomatically. Surgical excision remains curative.<br><br>Fibroma (option A) results from irritation; leukoplakia (option C) is premalignant; traumatic ulcer (option B) follows injury; ranula (option E) is mucous retention cyst. Therefore papilloma shows strongest HPV relation.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless ulceroproliferative lesion over floor of mouth in a chronic smoker should be considered:",o:["Aphthous ulcer","Squamous cell carcinoma","Oral candidiasis","Vincent angina","Tuberculous ulcer"],a:1,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits painless ulceroproliferative lesions over the floor of mouth in chronic smokers; characteristic high-risk oral malignancy presentation. Cervical nodal spread develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard pathology: carcinogenic exposure produces epithelial dysplasia and invasive malignant transformation symptomatically. Floor of mouth lesions often behave aggressively.<br><br>Aphthous ulcers (option A) are painful; oral candidiasis (option C) forms plaques; Vincent angina (option D) causes gingival necrosis; tuberculous ulcers (option E) are undermined. Therefore smoker-associated proliferative ulcers strongly suggest carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred investigation for suspicious oral cavity tumors is:",o:["Plain X-ray","FNAC only","Incisional biopsy","ESR","Blood culture"],a:2,e:"Incisional biopsy fits the preferred investigation for suspicious oral cavity tumors; characteristic definitive method for histopathologic diagnosis. Early confirmation improves clinically treatment outcomes.<br><br>Standard oncology practice requires tissue diagnosis before surgery or radiotherapy symptomatically. Histologic grading additionally guides prognosis and staging.<br><br>Plain X-ray (option A) lacks tissue detail; FNAC only (option B) inadequately samples mucosa; ESR (option D) and blood culture (option E) provide nonspecific information. Therefore biopsy remains essential.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common benign tumor arising from adipose tissue in oral cavity is:",o:["Papilloma","Hemangioma","Osteoma","Fibroma","Lipoma"],a:4,e:"Lipoma fits the common benign adipose tissue tumor of the oral cavity; characteristic soft yellowish submucosal swelling. Slow enlargement develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: mature adipocyte proliferation forms encapsulated lesions beneath oral mucosa symptomatically. Surgical excision usually remains curative.<br><br>Papilloma (option A) is epithelial; hemangioma (option B) is vascular; fibroma (option D) is connective tissue proliferation; osteoma (option C) is bony. Therefore lipoma represents benign adipose tumors.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"Oral submucous fibrosis is strongly associated with:",o:["Betel nut chewing","Tobacco smoking only","Viral infection","Alcohol alone","Poor dental hygiene only"],a:0,e:"Betel nut chewing fits the strongest association with oral submucous fibrosis; characteristic chronic progressive fibrotic oral mucosal disease. Restricted mouth opening develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard pathology: areca nut alkaloids stimulate collagen deposition and mucosal fibrosis symptomatically. Malignant transformation risk remains increased.<br><br>Tobacco smoking only (option B), viral infection (option C), alcohol alone (option D), and poor dental hygiene only (option E) lack equally strong association. Therefore betel nut exposure remains principal cause.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A dome-shaped bluish swelling in floor of mouth caused by mucus retention is called:",o:["Ranula","Fibroma","Papilloma","Hemangioma","Leukoplakia"],a:0,e:"Ranula fits dome-shaped bluish swellings in the floor of mouth caused by mucus retention from sublingual glands. Speech discomfort develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Standard pathology: salivary duct obstruction allows mucus extravasation into surrounding soft tissues symptomatically. Lesions appear translucent and fluctuant.<br><br>Fibroma (option B) is firm connective tissue growth; papilloma (option C) is papillary; hemangioma (option D) is vascular; leukoplakia (option E) forms white plaques. Therefore mucus retention cysts are termed ranulas.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important prognostic factor in oral cavity carcinoma is:",o:["Patient age","Tumor color","Cervical lymph node metastasis","Presence of pain","Duration of ulcer only"],a:2,e:"Cervical lymph node metastasis fits the most important prognostic factor in oral cavity carcinoma; characteristic marker of advanced disease spread. Survival decreases clinically significantly after nodal involvement.<br><br>Standard oncology staging heavily depends on regional lymphatic dissemination and extracapsular extension symptomatically. Early detection improves prognosis markedly.<br><br>Patient age (option A), tumor color (option B), presence of pain (option D), and ulcer duration only (option E) carry less prognostic significance. Therefore nodal metastasis most strongly influences outcome.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A pedunculated painless lesion with finger-like projections over oral mucosa is most likely:",o:["Lipoma","Papilloma","Fibrosarcoma","Squamous carcinoma","Ranula"],a:1,e:"Papilloma fits pedunculated oral lesions with finger-like projections; characteristic benign epithelial proliferation associated with HPV infection. Slow enlargement develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: papillary epithelial hyperplasia forms fibrovascular projections covered by stratified squamous epithelium symptomatically. Surgical removal usually cures disease completely.<br><br>Lipoma (option A) appears soft and yellow; fibrosarcoma (option C) is malignant connective tissue tumor; squamous carcinoma (option D) ulcerates; ranula (option E) is cystic. Therefore papillary projections strongly indicate papilloma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral cavity site with poorest prognosis for squamous cell carcinoma is the:",o:["Upper lip","Buccal mucosa","Gingiva","Hard palate","Floor of mouth"],a:4,e:"Floor of mouth carcinoma fits oral cancers with particularly poor prognosis; characteristic early infiltration and lymphatic spread. Cervical metastasis develops clinically relatively early.<br><br>Standard pathology: thin mucosa and rich lymphatic drainage facilitate rapid invasive spread symptomatically. Delayed presentation worsens survival outcomes.<br><br>Upper lip (option A), buccal mucosa (option B), hard palate (option D), and gingiva (option C) generally show comparatively better prognosis. Therefore floor of mouth lesions behave aggressively.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The benign salivary gland tumor most likely to undergo malignant transformation is:",o:["Hemangioma","Lipoma","Fibroma","Papilloma","Pleomorphic adenoma"],a:4,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma fits the benign salivary tumor most likely to undergo malignant transformation; characteristic long-standing mixed salivary neoplasm. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>Standard pathology: epithelial and stromal proliferation may eventually transform into carcinoma ex pleomorphic adenoma symptomatically. Long duration increases malignant risk.<br><br>Hemangioma (option A), lipoma (option B), papilloma (option D), and fibroma (option C) rarely undergo malignant transformation. Therefore pleomorphic adenoma requires complete excision.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with oral submucous fibrosis commonly presents with:",o:["Excessive salivation","Hearing loss","Nasal obstruction","Restricted mouth opening","Epistaxis"],a:3,e:"Restricted mouth opening fits oral submucous fibrosis; characteristic progressive fibrotic stiffening of oral mucosa. Burning sensation develops clinically during spicy food intake.<br><br>Standard pathology: excessive collagen deposition reduces mucosal elasticity and oral mobility symptomatically. Malignant transformation risk remains elevated.<br><br>Excessive salivation (option A), nasal obstruction (option C), hearing loss (option B), and epistaxis (option E) are unrelated features. Therefore trismus-like limitation strongly suggests submucous fibrosis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant salivary gland tumor affecting oral cavity minor salivary glands is:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Mucoepidermoid carcinoma","Warthin tumor","Lipoma","Hemangioma"],a:1,e:"Mucoepidermoid carcinoma fits the commonest malignant salivary gland tumor involving oral minor salivary glands; characteristic variable cystic and solid growth. Palatal swelling develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: mucous and epidermoid cell proliferation forms malignant salivary neoplasms with variable aggressiveness symptomatically. Histologic grade determines prognosis.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A) is benign; Warthin tumor (option C) mainly affects parotid gland; lipoma (option D) is adipose tissue tumor; hemangioma (option E) is vascular. Therefore mucoepidermoid carcinoma predominates among malignant salivary tumors.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The nerve carrying taste sensation from anterior two-thirds of tongue is the:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Lingual nerve","Chorda tympani","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:2,e:"Chorda tympani fits taste supply of the anterior two-thirds of tongue; characteristic branch of facial nerve traveling with lingual nerve. Taste disturbance develops clinically after middle ear surgery.<br><br>Standard anatomy: special sensory fibers join the lingual nerve before reaching facial nerve pathways symptomatically. General sensation remains separately supplied by trigeminal fibers.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A) supplies posterior tongue taste; lingual nerve (option B) carries general sensation; hypoglossal nerve (option D) supplies motor function; vagus nerve (option E) supplies epiglottic region. Therefore chorda tympani transmits taste fibers.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fever, trismus, muffled voice, and uvular deviation most likely has:",o:["Ludwig angina","Acute epiglottitis","Oral candidiasis","Retropharyngeal abscess","Peritonsillar abscess"],a:4,e:"Peritonsillar abscess fits fever with trismus, muffled \"hot potato\" voice, and contralateral uvular deviation; characteristic quinsy presentation. Odynophagia becomes clinically severe.<br><br>Standard pathology: suppuration develops between tonsillar capsule and superior constrictor muscle following acute tonsillitis symptomatically. Airway compromise may occur in advanced disease.<br><br>Ludwig angina (option A) causes bilateral submandibular swelling; acute epiglottitis (option B) presents with stridor; retropharyngeal abscess (option D) causes posterior wall bulging; oral candidiasis (option C) forms plaques. Therefore findings strongly suggest peritonsillar abscess.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common premalignant lesion of oral cavity repeatedly asked in FCPS recalls is:",o:["Oral candidiasis","Leukoplakia","Herpetic stomatitis","Aphthous ulcer","Ranula"],a:1,e:"Leukoplakia fits the commonest premalignant oral cavity lesion; characteristic persistent white nonscrapable mucosal patch. Malignant transformation develops clinically in dysplastic lesions.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic carcinogenic exposure produces epithelial hyperplasia and varying grades of dysplasia symptomatically. Histologic assessment guides prognosis.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option A) forms removable plaques; herpetic stomatitis (option C) is viral; aphthous ulcers (option D) are inflammatory; ranula (option E) is cystic. Therefore leukoplakia remains the principal premalignant lesion.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of oral cavity carcinoma in betel nut chewers is the:",o:["Hard palate","Floor of mouth","Buccal mucosa","Dorsum of tongue","Tonsillar pillar"],a:2,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest oral cavity carcinoma site in betel nut chewers; characteristic chronic mucosal carcinogen exposure. Nonhealing ulcers develop clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: repeated epithelial irritation induces dysplasia progressing toward invasive squamous carcinoma symptomatically. Cervical nodal metastasis may occur early.<br><br>Hard palate (option A), floor of mouth (option B), tongue dorsum (option D), and tonsillar pillar (option E) are comparatively less affected regionally. Therefore buccal mucosa remains the predominant site.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A chronic painless indurated ulcer on lateral border of tongue should be considered:",o:["Aphthous ulcer","Tuberculous ulcer","Traumatic ulcer","Herpetic ulcer","Squamous cell carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits chronic painless indurated ulcers involving the lateral tongue border; characteristic malignant oral lesion presentation. Cervical lymph node metastasis develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard pathology: invasive epithelial malignancy causes ulceration with rolled margins and tissue destruction symptomatically. Tobacco exposure strongly increases risk.<br><br>Aphthous ulcers (option A) are painful and recurrent; tuberculous ulcers (option B) show undermined edges; herpetic ulcers (option D) follow vesicles; traumatic ulcers (option C) heal after irritation removal. Therefore induration strongly suggests carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The floor of mouth is primarily formed by the:",o:["Buccinator muscle","Masseter muscle","Mylohyoid muscle","Hyoglossus muscle","Temporalis muscle"],a:2,e:"Mylohyoid muscle fits the principal muscular floor of the oral cavity; characteristic diaphragm-like support beneath the tongue. Infection spread occurs clinically through related fascial spaces.<br><br>Standard anatomy: paired mylohyoid muscles extend between mandible and hyoid bone forming oral floor structures symptomatically. Sublingual glands lie superiorly.<br><br>Buccinator muscle (option A) forms cheek wall; masseter muscle (option B) elevates mandible; hyoglossus muscle (option D) depresses tongue; temporalis muscle (option E) assists mastication. Therefore mylohyoid forms the oral cavity floor.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fever, bilateral submandibular swelling, drooling, and tongue elevation after molar infection most likely has:",o:["Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Vincent angina","Acute tonsillitis","Ludwig angina"],a:4,e:"Ludwig angina fits bilateral submandibular swelling with tongue elevation and drooling following dental infection; characteristic rapidly progressive cellulitis. Airway obstruction develops clinically urgently.<br><br>Standard pathology: infection spreads through submandibular and sublingual fascial spaces causing diffuse edema symptomatically. Emergency airway management may become necessary.<br><br>Peritonsillar abscess (option A) causes uvular deviation; retropharyngeal abscess (option B) affects posterior pharynx; acute tonsillitis (option D) involves tonsils; Vincent angina (option C) affects gingiva. Therefore findings strongly indicate Ludwig angina.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral lesion with highest malignant transformation potential is:",o:["Leukoplakia","Aphthous ulcer","Papilloma","Fibroma","Erythroplakia"],a:4,e:"Erythroplakia fits the oral lesion with highest malignant transformation potential; characteristic red velvety mucosal patch frequently showing severe dysplasia. Biopsy becomes clinically essential.<br><br>Standard pathology: epithelial atypia and carcinoma in situ commonly occur within erythroplakic lesions symptomatically. Malignant progression rates exceed leukoplakia significantly.<br><br>Leukoplakia (option A) remains premalignant but less aggressive; aphthous ulcers (option B) are inflammatory; fibroma (option D) is reactive; papilloma (option C) is benign. Therefore erythroplakia carries greatest malignant risk.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful oral ulcers, genital ulcers, and uveitis most likely has:",o:["Behçet disease","Syphilis","Diphtheria","Tuberculosis","Herpangina"],a:0,e:"Behçet disease fits recurrent oral ulcers associated with genital ulcers and uveitis; characteristic multisystem vasculitic disorder. Painful mucosal lesions recur clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: immune-mediated vascular inflammation affects oral, ocular, and genital tissues symptomatically. Neurological complications may additionally occur.<br><br>Syphilis (option B) produces chancre; diphtheria (option C) forms pseudomembranes; tuberculosis (option D) causes undermined ulcers; herpangina (option E) causes vesicles. Therefore recurrent multisystem ulceration suggests Behçet disease.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common benign tumor of oral cavity is:",o:["Papilloma","Lipoma","Hemangioma","Fibroma","Osteoma"],a:3,e:"Fibroma fits the commonest benign oral cavity tumor; characteristic reactive connective tissue proliferation secondary to chronic irritation. Slow enlargement develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: fibroblastic overgrowth forms firm smooth mucosal nodules covered by intact epithelium symptomatically. Surgical excision remains curative.<br><br>Papilloma (option A) is epithelial; lipoma (option B) is adipose tissue tumor; hemangioma (option C) is vascular; osteoma (option E) is bony. Therefore fibroma predominates among benign oral tumors.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The lymphatic drainage from tip of tongue primarily goes to the:",o:["Deep cervical nodes","Jugulodigastric nodes","Submental nodes","Retropharyngeal nodes","Preauricular nodes"],a:2,e:"Submental lymph nodes fit the primary drainage pathway of the tongue tip; characteristic anterior oral cavity lymphatic pattern. Bilateral spread develops clinically in malignancies.<br><br>Standard anatomy: rich lymphatic communication allows early nodal metastasis from anterior tongue lesions symptomatically. Careful neck examination remains important.<br><br>Deep cervical nodes (option A) drain posterior tongue; jugulodigastric nodes (option B) drain tonsils; retropharyngeal nodes (option D) drain nasopharynx; preauricular nodes (option E) drain face. Therefore tongue tip drains mainly to submental nodes.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A gray adherent membrane over tonsils that bleeds on removal is characteristic of:",o:["Oral candidiasis","Herpetic stomatitis","Vincent angina","Aphthous ulcer","Diphtheria"],a:4,e:"Diphtheria fits gray adherent tonsillar membranes bleeding on attempted removal; characteristic toxin-mediated upper airway infection. Cervical swelling develops clinically in severe disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: Corynebacterium diphtheriae exotoxin causes epithelial necrosis and fibrinous pseudomembrane formation symptomatically. Myocarditis may complicate infection.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option A) forms removable plaques; herpetic stomatitis (option B) produces vesicles; aphthous ulcers (option D) are shallow ulcers; Vincent angina (option C) causes necrotic gingivitis. Therefore bleeding pseudomembranes indicate diphtheria.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The muscle responsible for protrusion of tongue is the:",o:["Hyoglossus","Styloglossus","Palatoglossus","Genioglossus","Buccinator"],a:3,e:"Genioglossus fits the principal protruder muscle of the tongue; characteristic fan-shaped extrinsic tongue muscle. Bilateral paralysis causes clinically dangerous airway obstruction.<br><br>Standard anatomy: genioglossus originates from genial tubercle and advances tongue anteriorly symptomatically. It maintains airway patency during sleep.<br><br>Hyoglossus (option A) depresses tongue; styloglossus (option B) retracts tongue; palatoglossus (option C) elevates posterior tongue; buccinator (option E) forms cheek musculature. Therefore genioglossus protrudes the tongue.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent painful oral ulcers healing without scarring most likely has:",o:["Aphthous stomatitis","Tuberculous ulcer","Squamous carcinoma","Syphilitic chancre","Leukoplakia"],a:0,e:"Aphthous stomatitis fits recurrent painful oral ulcers healing without scarring; characteristic immune-mediated mucosal disorder. Eating spicy food worsens clinically discomfort.<br><br>Standard pathology: superficial mucosal inflammation produces shallow ulcers surrounded by erythematous halo symptomatically. Stress and nutritional deficiencies may precipitate attacks.<br><br>Tuberculous ulcers (option B) are chronic; squamous carcinoma (option C) is indurated; syphilitic chancre (option D) is painless; leukoplakia (option E) forms white plaques. Therefore recurrent painful ulcers indicate aphthous disease.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Oral submucous fibrosis is strongly associated with:",o:["Cigarette smoking only","Viral infection","Betel nut chewing","Alcohol alone","Dental caries only"],a:2,e:"Betel nut chewing fits the strongest association with oral submucous fibrosis; characteristic chronic progressive fibrotic oral mucosal disease. Restricted mouth opening develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: areca nut alkaloids stimulate collagen deposition and mucosal fibrosis symptomatically. Malignant transformation risk remains increased.<br><br>Cigarette smoking only (option A), viral infection (option B), alcohol alone (option D), and dental caries only (option E) lack comparable association. Therefore betel nut exposure remains the principal cause.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A bluish translucent swelling in floor of mouth caused by mucus retention is called:",o:["Papilloma","Ranula","Fibroma","Hemangioma","Leukoplakia"],a:1,e:"Ranula fits bluish translucent swellings in the floor of mouth caused by mucus extravasation from salivary glands. Speech discomfort develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Standard pathology: obstruction or trauma to sublingual gland ducts permits mucus accumulation within surrounding tissues symptomatically. Lesions appear fluctuant and cystic.<br><br>Papilloma (option A) is papillary; fibroma (option C) is firm connective tissue growth; hemangioma (option D) is vascular; leukoplakia (option E) forms white plaques. Therefore mucus retention cysts are termed ranulas.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The posterior one-third of tongue receives sensory supply mainly from the:",o:["Facial nerve","Lingual nerve","Vagus nerve only","Hypoglossal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],a:4,e:"Glossopharyngeal nerve fits both general and taste sensory supply of the posterior one-third of tongue; characteristic dual sensory function. Referred otalgia develops clinically in lesions.<br><br>Standard anatomy: sensory fibers pass through glossopharyngeal pathways toward brainstem nuclei symptomatically. Gag reflex also involves this nerve.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A) supplies anterior tongue taste; lingual nerve (option B) supplies anterior sensation; hypoglossal nerve (option D) is motor; vagus nerve only (option C) supplies epiglottic region. Therefore glossopharyngeal nerve innervates posterior tongue sensation.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with HIV develops corrugated white plaques over lateral tongue that cannot be scraped off. The diagnosis is:",o:["Oral candidiasis","Herpangina","Aphthous ulcer","Hairy leukoplakia","Diphtheria"],a:3,e:"Hairy leukoplakia fits corrugated nonscrapable white plaques over lateral tongue in HIV patients; characteristic Epstein-Barr virus-associated lesion. Painless mucosal changes develop clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: viral epithelial hyperplasia produces thickened corrugated white mucosa symptomatically. Lesions differ from candidiasis by adherence.<br><br>Oral candidiasis (option A) forms removable plaques; aphthous ulcers (option C) are painful erosions; herpangina (option B) causes vesicles; diphtheria (option E) forms pseudomembranes. Therefore lateral tongue plaques suggest hairy leukoplakia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cause of traumatic oral ulcer is:",o:["Tuberculosis","Viral infection","Fungal infection","Syphilis","Sharp tooth edge"],a:4,e:"Sharp tooth edges fit the commonest cause of traumatic oral ulcers; characteristic repeated mucosal irritation from damaged teeth. Pain worsens clinically during chewing.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic mechanical trauma produces epithelial breakdown and localized inflammatory ulceration symptomatically. Healing usually follows irritant removal.<br><br>Tuberculosis (option A), viral infection (option B), syphilis (option D), and fungal infection (option C) produce infectious lesions rather than traumatic ulcers. Therefore sharp teeth commonly cause traumatic ulcers.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important prognostic factor in oral cavity carcinoma is:",o:["Patient age","Tumor color","Cervical nodal metastasis","Presence of pain","Duration of lesion only"],a:2,e:"Cervical nodal metastasis fits the most important prognostic factor in oral cavity carcinoma; characteristic marker of advanced malignant spread. Survival decreases clinically significantly after nodal involvement.<br><br>Standard oncology staging heavily depends on regional lymphatic dissemination and extracapsular extension symptomatically. Early diagnosis improves prognosis markedly.<br><br>Patient age (option A), tumor color (option B), presence of pain (option D), and lesion duration only (option E) carry less prognostic importance. Therefore cervical nodal spread most strongly affects outcome.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The submandibular duct opens into oral cavity at the:",o:["Circumvallate papilla","Foramen cecum","Sublingual papilla","Hard palate","Retromolar trigone"],a:2,e:"Sublingual papilla fits the opening site of the submandibular duct beside the lingual frenulum; characteristic anatomical landmark. Salivary flow becomes clinically visible during examination.<br><br>Standard anatomy: Wharton duct courses anteriorly through floor of mouth before opening near tongue base symptomatically. Obstruction may produce painful swelling.<br><br>Circumvallate papilla (option A) contains taste buds; foramen cecum (option B) marks thyroid origin; hard palate (option D) forms oral roof; retromolar trigone (option E) lies posteriorly. Therefore the duct opens at sublingual papilla.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe foul breath, necrotic gingiva, and punched-out ulcers most likely has:",o:["Aphthous stomatitis","Syphilis","Oral candidiasis","Diphtheria","Vincent angina"],a:4,e:"Vincent angina fits foul breath with punched-out gingival ulcers and necrosis; characteristic acute necrotizing ulcerative gingivitis presentation. Gingival bleeding develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: fusospirochetal infection causes necrosis of interdental papillae and surrounding gingiva symptomatically. Poor oral hygiene strongly predisposes disease.<br><br>Aphthous stomatitis (option A) forms shallow ulcers; oral candidiasis (option C) produces white plaques; diphtheria (option D) forms pseudomembranes; syphilis (option B) causes painless chancre. Therefore necrotic fetid ulcers indicate Vincent angina.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral cavity lesion most associated with HPV infection is:",o:["Fibroma","Ranula","Leukoplakia","Lipoma","Papilloma"],a:4,e:"Papilloma fits the oral cavity lesion most strongly associated with HPV infection; characteristic exophytic papillary epithelial proliferation. Small painless masses develop clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: HPV-induced epithelial hyperplasia forms finger-like fibrovascular projections symptomatically. Surgical excision usually cures disease.<br><br>Fibroma (option A) results from chronic irritation; ranula (option B) is cystic; lipoma (option D) arises from adipose tissue; leukoplakia (option C) is premalignant. Therefore papilloma shows strongest HPV association.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful grouped oral vesicles followed by ulcers most likely has:",o:["Herpetic stomatitis","Aphthous ulcer","Syphilitic ulcer","Tuberculous ulcer","Leukoplakia"],a:0,e:"Herpetic stomatitis fits painful grouped oral vesicles progressing to ulceration; characteristic herpes simplex virus infection presentation. Fever develops clinically before lesions appear.<br><br>Standard pathology: viral cytopathic injury causes vesicle formation and epithelial destruction symptomatically. Primary infections are often severe in children.<br><br>Aphthous ulcers (option B) lack vesicular stage; syphilitic ulcers (option C) are painless; tuberculous ulcers (option D) remain chronic; leukoplakia (option E) forms white plaques. Therefore grouped vesicles indicate herpes infection.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The arterial supply of tongue is mainly derived from the:",o:["Facial artery","Maxillary artery","Lingual artery","Ascending pharyngeal artery","Superficial temporal artery"],a:2,e:"Lingual artery fits the principal arterial supply of the tongue; characteristic branch arising from the external carotid artery. Significant bleeding develops clinically after tongue injuries.<br><br>Standard anatomy: the artery courses deep to hyoglossus muscle supplying intrinsic and extrinsic tongue tissues symptomatically. Surgical procedures require careful preservation.<br><br>Facial artery (option A) supplies lips and face; maxillary artery (option B) supplies deep facial structures; ascending pharyngeal artery (option D) supplies pharynx; superficial temporal artery (option E) supplies scalp. Therefore lingual artery primarily nourishes the tongue.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with unilateral indurated ulcer over posterior lateral tongue and referred otalgia. The referred pain is mediated through the:",o:["Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Greater auricular nerve"],a:3,e:"Glossopharyngeal nerve fits referred otalgia from posterior tongue malignancy; characteristic shared sensory supply between tongue base and middle ear pathways. Cervical nodal spread develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard anatomy: glossopharyngeal afferents supply posterior tongue, tonsillar region, and middle ear mucosa symptomatically. Irritation therefore produces ear pain without primary ear disease.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A) mainly supplies facial muscles; hypoglossal nerve (option B) is motor; lingual nerve (option C) supplies anterior tongue sensation; greater auricular nerve (option E) supplies neck skin. Therefore glossopharyngeal nerve mediates referred pain.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with oral submucous fibrosis is at greatest risk of developing:",o:["Adenocarcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Fibrosarcoma"],a:1,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits the major malignant risk associated with oral submucous fibrosis; characteristic progression following chronic epithelial irritation and fibrosis. Restricted mouth opening develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: areca nut exposure induces collagen deposition with epithelial dysplasia and eventual invasive transformation symptomatically. Careful surveillance remains essential.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma (option A), basal cell carcinoma (option C), melanoma (option D), and fibrosarcoma (option E) show weaker associations with submucous fibrosis. Therefore squamous malignancy predominates.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A painful ulcer over tongue with undermined edges and associated pulmonary symptoms is most suggestive of:",o:["Traumatic ulcer","Aphthous ulcer","Verrucous carcinoma","Syphilitic chancre","Tuberculous ulcer"],a:4,e:"Tuberculous ulcers fit painful tongue lesions with undermined edges and concurrent pulmonary symptoms; characteristic secondary oral tuberculosis presentation. Weight loss develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: granulomatous inflammation with caseation necrosis produces chronic ulcerative mucosal destruction symptomatically. Pulmonary infection commonly acts as primary focus.<br><br>Traumatic ulcers (option A) heal after irritant removal; aphthous ulcers (option B) are recurrent superficial lesions; syphilitic chancres (option D) remain painless; verrucous carcinoma (option C) is exophytic. Therefore chronic undermined ulcers suggest tuberculosis.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of minor salivary gland tumors within oral cavity is the:",o:["Tongue tip","Buccal sulcus","Hard palate","Lower lip","Retromolar trigone"],a:2,e:"Hard palate fits the commonest site of minor salivary gland tumors within the oral cavity; characteristic abundance of mucous glands in palatal mucosa. Painless swelling develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard anatomy: numerous minor salivary glands occupy posterior lateral hard palate regions symptomatically. Both benign and malignant tumors may arise there.<br><br>Tongue tip (option A), buccal sulcus (option B), lower lip (option D), and retromolar trigone (option E) contain comparatively fewer minor salivary glands. Therefore palatal involvement predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe oral candidiasis following prolonged antibiotic therapy most likely has overgrowth of:",o:["Aspergillus fumigatus","Candida albicans","Treponema pallidum","Herpes simplex virus","Actinomyces israelii"],a:1,e:"Candida albicans fits severe oral candidiasis following prolonged antibiotic therapy; characteristic opportunistic fungal overgrowth after normal flora suppression. Burning oral discomfort develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: altered oral microbial balance permits fungal proliferation producing white pseudomembranous plaques symptomatically. Lesions leave erythematous mucosa after scraping.<br><br>Aspergillus fumigatus (option A) primarily affects respiratory tract; Treponema pallidum (option C) causes syphilis; herpes simplex virus (option D) produces vesicles; Actinomyces israelii (option E) causes cervicofacial actinomycosis. Therefore Candida predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral cavity cancer with highest incidence of bilateral cervical nodal metastasis is carcinoma of the:",o:["Upper lip","Buccal mucosa","Tongue tip","Floor of mouth","Hard palate"],a:3,e:"Floor of mouth carcinoma fits oral cancers with particularly high bilateral nodal metastasis risk; characteristic rich cross-midline lymphatic drainage. Prognosis worsens clinically after nodal spread.<br><br>Standard pathology: thin mucosa and abundant lymphatic channels facilitate rapid dissemination of malignant cells symptomatically. Early detection significantly improves survival.<br><br>Upper lip (option A), buccal mucosa (option B), tongue tip (option C), and hard palate (option E) generally show comparatively lower bilateral spread. Therefore floor of mouth lesions behave aggressively.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A recurrent painful ulcer larger than 1 cm healing with scarring is classified as:",o:["Minor aphthous ulcer","Herpetiform ulcer","Syphilitic ulcer","Traumatic ulcer","Major aphthous ulcer"],a:4,e:"Major aphthous ulcers fit recurrent painful lesions larger than one centimeter healing with scarring; characteristic severe aphthous stomatitis subtype. Swallowing difficulty develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: deeper mucosal inflammation produces prolonged ulceration and fibrosis during healing symptomatically. Episodes may persist for several weeks.<br><br>Minor aphthous ulcers (option A) heal rapidly without scars; herpetiform ulcers (option B) are multiple tiny lesions; traumatic ulcers (option D) follow irritation; syphilitic ulcers (option C) remain painless. Therefore scarring ulcers indicate major aphthae.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with oral ulceration and target skin lesions most likely has:",o:["Behçet disease","Vincent angina","Oral candidiasis","Diphtheria","Erythema multiforme"],a:4,e:"Erythema multiforme fits oral ulceration associated with target-shaped skin lesions; characteristic hypersensitivity-mediated mucocutaneous disorder. Painful erosions develop clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard pathology: immune-mediated epithelial injury affects oral and cutaneous surfaces symptomatically. Drug reactions and herpes infections commonly precipitate episodes.<br><br>Behçet disease (option A) causes genital ulcers and uveitis; oral candidiasis (option C) forms plaques; diphtheria (option D) forms membranes; Vincent angina (option B) causes gingival necrosis. Therefore target lesions suggest erythema multiforme.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"During excision of submandibular gland, injury to which nerve causes loss of taste from anterior two-thirds of tongue?",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Facial nerve trunk","Lingual nerve carrying chorda tympani fibers"],a:4,e:"Lingual nerve carrying chorda tympani fibers fits taste loss after submandibular gland surgery; characteristic close anatomical relation with Wharton duct. Oral numbness develops clinically additionally.<br><br>Standard anatomy: chorda tympani joins the lingual nerve before entering floor of mouth structures symptomatically. Surgical trauma therefore affects taste and general sensation simultaneously.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A) supplies posterior tongue; hypoglossal nerve (option B) supplies motor function; facial nerve trunk (option D) lies distant; vagus nerve (option C) supplies pharyngeal structures. Therefore lingual nerve injury explains symptoms.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site for traumatic ulcers due to sharp molars is the:",o:["Hard palate","Lateral border of tongue","Soft palate","Upper gingiva","Tonsillar pillar"],a:1,e:"Lateral tongue border fits the commonest site for traumatic ulcers caused by sharp molars; characteristic repeated friction during mastication. Pain develops clinically during eating.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic mechanical irritation causes epithelial breakdown and inflammatory ulceration symptomatically. Persistent trauma may mimic malignancy.<br><br>Hard palate (option A), soft palate (option C), upper gingiva (option D), and tonsillar pillar (option E) experience comparatively less repetitive contact with molars. Therefore lateral tongue ulcers commonly result from dental trauma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with oral squamous carcinoma develops fixation of tongue movements. The muscle most likely infiltrated is the:",o:["Buccinator","Palatoglossus","Genioglossus","Mylohyoid","Orbicularis oris"],a:2,e:"Genioglossus infiltration fits fixation of tongue movements in advanced oral carcinoma; characteristic involvement of major extrinsic tongue muscle. Speech impairment develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Standard anatomy: genioglossus controls protrusion and contributes significantly to overall tongue mobility symptomatically. Deep invasion restricts oral function markedly.<br><br>Buccinator (option A) forms cheek wall; palatoglossus (option B) elevates posterior tongue; mylohyoid (option D) forms oral floor; orbicularis oris (option E) surrounds lips. Therefore genioglossus infiltration limits tongue movement.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A chronic oral ulcer with raised everted edges is most suggestive of:",o:["Syphilitic chancre","Tuberculous ulcer","Traumatic ulcer","Aphthous ulcer","Squamous cell carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits chronic ulcers with raised everted edges; characteristic malignant ulcer morphology. Cervical nodal enlargement develops clinically during progression.<br><br>Standard pathology: invasive epithelial malignancy destroys surrounding tissues producing induration and rolled margins symptomatically. Histologic confirmation remains essential.<br><br>Syphilitic chancres (option A) are painless and indurated; tuberculous ulcers (option B) have undermined edges; aphthous ulcers (option D) are shallow and painful; traumatic ulcers (option C) heal after irritant removal. Therefore everted margins suggest carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral lesion classically associated with Epstein-Barr virus in HIV patients is:",o:["Aphthous ulcer","Fibroma","Ranula","Papilloma","Hairy leukoplakia"],a:4,e:"Hairy leukoplakia fits Epstein-Barr virus-associated oral lesions in HIV patients; characteristic corrugated white plaques over lateral tongue. Lesions remain clinically painless usually.<br><br>Standard pathology: viral epithelial hyperplasia produces thickened nonscrapable white mucosal changes symptomatically. Immunosuppression strongly predisposes disease.<br><br>Aphthous ulcers (option A) are inflammatory; ranula (option C) is cystic; papilloma (option D) relates HPV infection; fibroma (option B) is reactive connective tissue proliferation. Therefore EBV commonly causes hairy leukoplakia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"The arterial supply to submandibular gland is mainly derived from branches of the:",o:["Lingual artery","Maxillary artery","Facial artery","Ascending pharyngeal artery","Superficial temporal artery"],a:2,e:"Facial artery fits the principal arterial supply of the submandibular gland; characteristic close anatomical relation during gland surgery. Significant bleeding develops clinically after injury.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial artery grooves the posterior gland surface before ascending onto the face symptomatically. Surgical preservation remains important.<br><br>Lingual artery (option A) mainly supplies tongue; maxillary artery (option B) supplies deep facial structures; ascending pharyngeal artery (option D) supplies pharynx; superficial temporal artery (option E) supplies scalp. Therefore facial artery nourishes the gland predominantly.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diffuse gingival hypertrophy and spontaneous bleeding should raise suspicion for:",o:["Leukemia","Syphilis","Diphtheria","Oral candidiasis","Tuberculosis"],a:0,e:"Leukemia fits diffuse gingival hypertrophy with spontaneous bleeding; characteristic infiltration of gingival tissues by malignant leukocytes. Fatigue develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Standard pathology: abnormal leukocyte proliferation causes mucosal infiltration and thrombocytopenia-related bleeding symptomatically. Oral findings may precede systemic diagnosis.<br><br>Syphilis (option B) causes chancre; diphtheria (option C) forms pseudomembranes; oral candidiasis (option D) forms plaques; tuberculosis (option E) causes chronic ulcers. Therefore gingival hypertrophy strongly suggests leukemia.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site for oral cavity minor aphthous ulcers is the:",o:["Attached gingiva","Hard palate","Floor of mouth only","Dorsum of tongue","Buccal mucosa"],a:4,e:"Buccal mucosa fits the commonest site for minor aphthous ulcers; characteristic involvement of nonkeratinized movable oral mucosa. Pain during eating develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: superficial immune-mediated ulceration affects delicate mucosal surfaces symptomatically. Lesions generally heal without scarring.<br><br>Attached gingiva (option A) and hard palate (option B) are keratinized; dorsum of tongue (option D) is less commonly involved; floor of mouth only (option C) is inaccurate. Therefore buccal mucosa predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with oral carcinoma develops numbness over lower lip. This finding suggests involvement of the:",o:["Lingual nerve","Mental nerve","Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Greater auricular nerve"],a:1,e:"Mental nerve involvement fits numbness over the lower lip in oral carcinoma; characteristic \"numb chin syndrome\" from mandibular invasion. Advanced local spread develops clinically significantly.<br><br>Standard anatomy: the mental nerve exits through the mental foramen supplying lower lip sensation symptomatically. Tumor infiltration interrupts sensory transmission.<br><br>Lingual nerve (option A) supplies tongue sensation; facial nerve (option C) controls facial muscles; glossopharyngeal nerve (option D) supplies posterior tongue; greater auricular nerve (option E) supplies neck skin. Therefore mental nerve damage explains symptoms.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest malignant tumor of minor salivary glands in oral cavity is:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Warthin tumor","Fibroma","Hemangioma","Mucoepidermoid carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Mucoepidermoid carcinoma fits the commonest malignant tumor affecting minor salivary glands within the oral cavity; characteristic palatal involvement. Painless swelling develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: mucous and epidermoid cell proliferation forms malignant salivary neoplasms with variable aggressiveness symptomatically. Histologic grading determines prognosis.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A) remains benign; Warthin tumor (option B) affects parotid gland; hemangioma (option D) is vascular; fibroma (option C) is reactive connective tissue growth. Therefore mucoepidermoid carcinoma predominates.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with oral ulceration after chemotherapy most likely has:",o:["Syphilis","Tuberculosis","Mucositis","Diphtheria","Herpangina"],a:2,e:"Mucositis fits painful oral ulceration occurring after chemotherapy; characteristic toxic injury to rapidly dividing oral epithelium. Severe odynophagia develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: cytotoxic drugs impair epithelial regeneration causing ulceration and inflammation symptomatically. Secondary infections may complicate lesions.<br><br>Syphilis (option A), tuberculosis (option B), diphtheria (option D), and herpangina (option E) represent infectious disorders rather than chemotherapy complications. Therefore mucositis commonly follows cytotoxic therapy.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important investigation for persistent leukoplakia is:",o:["Blood culture","ESR","FNAC only","Mantoux test","Incisional biopsy"],a:4,e:"Incisional biopsy fits the most important investigation for persistent leukoplakia; characteristic need to evaluate epithelial dysplasia and malignancy risk. Early diagnosis improves clinically outcomes significantly.<br><br>Standard pathology assessment determines severity of epithelial atypia and guides treatment planning symptomatically. Persistent lesions always require histologic confirmation.<br><br>Blood culture (option A), ESR (option B), and Mantoux test (option D) provide nonspecific information; FNAC only (option C) inadequately evaluates mucosal dysplasia. Therefore biopsy remains essential.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of syphilitic chancre in oral cavity is the:",o:["Hard palate","Tongue","Buccal mucosa","Lower lip","Gingiva"],a:3,e:"Lower lip fits the commonest oral site of syphilitic chancre; characteristic painless indurated ulcer occurring after primary infection. Regional lymphadenopathy develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: Treponema pallidum infection produces localized plasma cell-rich inflammatory lesions symptomatically. Spontaneous healing may occur despite persistent infection.<br><br>Hard palate (option A), tongue (option B), buccal mucosa (option C), and gingiva (option E) are comparatively less frequent sites. Therefore lower lip commonly develops chancre lesions.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A rapidly enlarging ulcerative lesion with fixation to underlying tissues in oral cavity most strongly suggests:",o:["Aphthous ulcer","Fibroma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Papilloma","Ranula"],a:2,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits rapidly enlarging ulcerative lesions fixed to underlying tissues; characteristic invasive malignant behavior. Cervical metastasis develops clinically relatively early.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant epithelial cells infiltrate surrounding structures producing induration and fixation symptomatically. Prompt biopsy becomes essential.<br><br>Aphthous ulcers (option A) heal spontaneously; fibroma (option B) remains benign; papilloma (option D) is exophytic; ranula (option E) is cystic. Therefore invasive fixation strongly indicates carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The lymph node most commonly involved first in carcinoma of posterior tongue is the:",o:["Submental node","Preauricular node","Paratracheal node","Occipital node","Jugulodigastric node"],a:4,e:"Jugulodigastric lymph node fits the first nodal station commonly involved in posterior tongue carcinoma; characteristic drainage pattern of oropharyngeal tongue. Metastasis develops clinically early.<br><br>Standard anatomy: posterior tongue lymphatics drain primarily toward upper deep cervical nodal groups symptomatically. Bilateral spread may occur rapidly.<br><br>Submental nodes (option A) drain tongue tip; preauricular nodes (option B) drain facial regions; occipital nodes (option D) drain scalp; paratracheal nodes (option C) drain airway structures. Therefore jugulodigastric nodes are commonly affected first.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent oral ulcers and malabsorption should be evaluated for deficiency of:",o:["Vitamin B12 and iron","Calcium only","Vitamin D only","Sodium only","Potassium only"],a:0,e:"Vitamin B12 and iron deficiency fit recurrent oral ulcers associated with malabsorption syndromes; characteristic nutritional contribution to aphthous disease. Burning tongue sensation develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: epithelial turnover impairment and immune dysfunction predispose recurrent mucosal ulceration symptomatically. Nutritional correction often reduces recurrences.<br><br>Calcium only (option B), vitamin D only (option C), sodium only (option D), and potassium only (option E) show weaker associations with recurrent aphthous ulceration. Therefore hematinic deficiencies warrant evaluation.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The oral cavity structure most commonly injured during lower third molar extraction is the:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Facial nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:2,e:"Lingual nerve fits the structure most commonly injured during lower third molar extraction; characteristic close relation to mandibular molar region. Tongue numbness develops clinically after trauma.<br><br>Standard anatomy: the lingual nerve courses medially near mandibular molars carrying general sensation and taste fibers symptomatically. Surgical injury may impair taste additionally.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A) supplies posterior tongue; hypoglossal nerve (option B) is motor; facial nerve (option D) supplies facial muscles; vagus nerve (option E) supplies pharyngeal structures. Therefore lingual nerve injury commonly follows molar extraction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
];